I have returned to the franchise during Fifa 22; Played three three “seasons” of the Ultimate Team back to back.
I must say, this is hands down the worst experience I’ve had playing FIFA (or EA FC in the case) ever. 
The game is filled with bugs, poor gameplay (where everyone is just playing the same formation and doing cutbacks all game long) and constant errors by EA.
Last error completely killed Ultimate Team for the majority of people. Specifically, they have released an SBC where a lot of people ended up getting TOTY Messi for practically doing NOTHING but being the first ones to complete the SBC before it was removed. 
This is a huge disappointment to those who grind every single objective, every single game mode to get a good card into their team. Now, even in lower divisions, you have to face Messi, who is debatably one of the best cards atm.
So, huge thumbs down for the game and the company in charge; do not buy the game.

I’ll start this off by saying fc 24 is bad and not worth your money.

Ever since I bought this game I’ve been so confused as to the way my players perform.  I’ll watch other streamers, and albeit they have a hard time with the gameplay too, even their players seemed to move more fluidly than mine.  It was really making no sense, until I finally came and looked at the pc reviews I realized that the pc port is absolutely garbage. 

If you can actually get the game to launch properly, having to jump through a series of hurdles most times, you are faced with a horrible experience.  The gameplay on console is bad, it’s even worse on pc.  Playing online is seriously the most infuriating thing in my life.  I can barely get through a single rivals game without almost punching a hole in my drywall.  My players are constantly either skating on ice or moving through water.  Every touch is too heavy or just simply gets stuck at your feet.  Moving around on pc in this game feels absolutely atrocious.  

Skill moves simply won’t register, I don’t know how many times I’ve had to input the same skill move 3 times in a row just for my player to somehow fuck it up, a simple ball roll will fail to register 95% of the time.  

I don’t know how they did it, but somehow player switching is broken.  You will constantly switch to a player that is far removed from the play, making you move that player thinking it will switch to the cdm in front of the player with the ball.  This routinely causes you to move your players out of position leaving easy scoring opportunities.  You used to be able to counter this by directly switching with left stick but somehow they made this impossible. Want to switch from your cb to your cdm with a simple flick to the right? You are now controlling your left mid.  I don’t know how they did it, but somehow they made this impossible to navigate. 

Your keepers will not work.  Half the time they make a world class save, the other half the ball phases through their hands.  This game is so full of shitty, inconsistent garbage gameplay that not even ghandi could make it through a rivals match without wanting to kill someone. 

There are a whole host of other things I could get into, like the predatory gambling casino for minors lightly facaded as packs, but I’ll leave it there.  

The gameplay is shit, the content is shit, and ea are an irredeemable company, this is my last purchase of an ea game.

The physics are sometimes messed up, but it's still a pretty fun game, very similar to fifa 23, but with a bit slower gameplay and the addition of playstyles. Playstyles are a core mechanic of the game which separates it from the other fifa iterations and to me it is a very fun twist on the standard fifa gameplay formula. Simply put, every player now has their specialty on the pitch, sometimes being kind of ridiculous, other times maybe being a bit unnoticeable. Ultimate team is where the game really shines and the pay-to-win aspect isnt thaaat bad.

Great graphics and presentation. They have most of the teams licences (brazil and roma are missing). The PC control mappings sometimes bug out, but you can get around that. All in all its a good game, its just that to get to the fun part of the game, you need to go through all of EAs bullshit, which include the poor optimization, the pay-to-win packs and the very random and sometimes almost unexplainable bugs. Regardless, I would still recommend it, as it is the best football game out there unfortunately and it sometimes has its bright moments.

This is the first FIFA game I've ever played, and it will also be my last. The entire focus of this game revolves around Squad Building Challenges (SBCs) and completing objectives; progressing is nearly impossible without engaging in these features. If you're considering buying the game, I strongly advise against it at this point. It's already too late, as most players have acquired strong cards, making it difficult for newcomers to compete. Additionally, the game mechanics are complex, requiring a significant amount of time to learn. If you are new to FIFA, I recommend avoiding the purchase as it can be challenging to catch up and enjoy the experience.

EA have dropped the FIFA moniker after losing the naming rights and are now presenting their premier football franchise with a fresh look. Here are the pros and cons, cons first:

CONS
Possibly the worst gameplay of the FIFA franchise. Players move behind their markers consistently leading to needlessly lost possession, passes often lead to nothing, it takes an absurd amount of time to even get your FUT squad even to 86 unless you buy coins or points and any other modes besides FUT and Career Mode are akin to huffing pure carbon monoxide.

PROS
Menus look really nice, bugs aside. The redesign feels very fresh and clean, and the menus are newly optimised for lower end hardware in comparison to FIFA 23. Mods, as usual, heavily carry this game just like any other FIFA franchise game on PC. FIFER, RODE, WZRD and the eSIM projects are all worth looking into this year just like any other year and they all deliver well. The game has FAR better performance than 23 and even 22, leading to being able to run this on anything from lower mid end to the upper echelons of PC builds. Career mode feels roughly the same as 23, but that's not to discredit the mode. It still delivers (as long as you use mods) just like any other variant of it and there's lots of room for creativity. I haven't played Pro Clubs as of yet but I assume it offers much of the same as it always has, same goes for VOLTA this year.

THE VERDICT
Use the Anadius Denuvo workaround to play this game until you're 100% sure you want it, the gameplay is different enough from 23 for this to be kind of a neccessity. It runs far better than 23 but it still can have performance issues on very low end hardware. And of course, modding is the way to go as always.

I'd rather flush my money down the toilet than subject myself to the torturous experience of this so-called game. It's like the developers took a crash course in game design from a malfunctioning toaster.

I decided to give FC24 a chance after a two-year break from their games, thinking maybe they've improved. Big mistake. This game has done wonders for my stress levels – by which I mean it's elevated them to new heights. I should have stuck to my peaceful pastime of betting on turtle races; at least there, the unpredictability is intentional.

It's evident that EA has assembled a dream team of interns who must have learned game development through interpretive dance. I'm convinced they're using ChatGPT to code the entire mess. The gameplay is so scripted that I half-expect the players to break into a synchronized dance routine at any moment. I wont even lie when it comes to scoring goals against my opponent as I sometimes pity him and feel his distress from the shear cancer of this game.

And let's talk about the impeccable physics – or lack thereof. Suddenly, players move like they're carrying the weight of the world on their shoulders. It's like they're auditioning for a slow-motion ballet instead of playing a football game. Passing, tackles, and rebounds? Ah, who needs logical game mechanics when you can have chaos that feels completely AI-controlled?

In conclusion, FC24 is a masterpiece if you consider "masterpiece" to be a synonym for disaster. Save your money, buy a bag of popcorn, and watch turtle races instead – at least you'll get more excitement and a better return on your investment. There is no reason for you to wipe some years off of your life just to pursue the "perfect UT team" as if its going to make your life any better.

Same as ever. Minor, incremental and barely noticeable changes made to last year's game so that they can sell it again at AAA prices. This is the formula for these sports titles and EA FC is no different. On the plus side, the name change is just cosmetic... for all intents and purposes, this is the FIFA of old.

Judged solely on its merits, its not a bad game, UI is a bit different but plays like any old FIFA. Tons of fun to be had playing with friends and the cross-play feature is welcome in that respect. 

Ultimately, however, this game should not be published annually, rather every few years with annual updates and player packs. The "improvements" year on year do not justify EA selling it as a brand new game. Only worth buying if the last FIFA you played was 5+ years ago.

Honestly this game is waste of money. I am a single player who likes to play career mode, therefore I will only comment on single player element of this game. 

As you play this game in career mode, you face an obstacle that inhibits you from enjoying this game, which is difficulty. The problem is that this game does not know how to properly balance the game play. When placed on easy difficulty, all the AI opponents do not play defense and let you run through them like they are bystander. The bigger problem rises when you actually want challenge. When you go for higher difficulty, all of sudden you face dumbed down teammates, not sophisticated opponents. To watch 3 defenders practicing social distancing on 1 opponent, refusing to contain or tackle him is plain brain cancer experience that you get to witness the entirety of the game. I honestly do not understand how does EA Sports keep releasing basically same game over and over every year without putting in actual improvement to their AI opponents and teammates.

My advise to anyone who might be considering buy this game is do not waste your money on glorified 3D soccer animator. I promise you, only difference between previous Fifa game and this is updated roster.

[b]Resum: Jugueu a Football Life 2024[/b] (www . pessmokepatch . com / 2023 / 09 / spfl24 . html)

He provat el joc unes hores gràcies al cap de setmana de joc gratuït de Gener del 2024.
L'últim FIFA que havia jugat amb regularitat abans del canvi de nom de la franquícia fou el FIFA 18. L'altre dia revisant la nova aplicació d'EA per escriptori em vaig informar que hi havia jugat 1008 hores. És un joc que tot i allunyar-se bastant de la simulació i apropar-se molt més a l'[i]arcade[/i] em divertia prou com per seguir jugant a estones.

L'EA FC 24 em sembla una evolució d'aquell joc. I això no és necessàriament quelcom positiu. Han passat bastants anys, i és en essència el mateix joc, però m'ha resultat molt menys divertit. Hi he detectat moltes més animacions. D'algunes curioses com que els jugadors es col·loquen les mans al darrere automàticament quan defensen dins de l'àrea, que ajuden a millorar la versemblança amb la realitat. D'altres amb una intenció, entenc que més pràctica com les diferents formes d'acompanyar la pilota amb els peus mentre s'avança ja sigui caminant o corrents. Però de fet, no aporten canvis substancials. 
El joc continua sent totalment [i]arcade[/i], fins al punt que em sembla encara més [i]arcade[/i] que a l'edició anterior que havia jugat. És molt difícil simular el futbol real, moure la pilota correctament, fer la passada en el moment correcte de la desmarcada, etc. perquè al meu parer la intel·ligència dels jugadors del mateix equip no controlats per l'usuari no actua simulant la realitat en dificultats mitjanes. A més a més en dificultats elevades els rivals, l'equip no controlat pel jugador, son completament perfectes i en dificultats inferiors simplement no competeixen, van caminant pel camp badant boca.
Tot i provar les diferents tàctiques de plantilla que ofereix el joc, un cop al camp les diferències són ridícules. Els davanters queden totalment en línia amb els defenses sense oferir desmarcades, el migcamp no es mou i els defenses actuen de manera automàtica. Defensar és complicat i requereix d'una precisió incòmode ja que la càmera és massa lluny de l'acció, i ho ha de ser per poder veure tot el camp, canviar a una càmera més propera, fa que es perdi el joc tàctic per la visió reduïda, i tampoc millora massa l'habilitat defensiva. Caldria replantejar, al meu parer, la interacció necessària del jugador perquè senti diversió enlloc de frustració a l'hora de defensar. 

Penso també que el joc està excessivament pre-configurat o automatitzat. Les accions del joc no son el resultat d'una simulació lliure sinó que tenen paràmetres (interns, amagats darrere de línies de codi) que controlen les possibilitats de manera, al meu parer, artificial. Això fa que en ocasions sigui frustrant jugar-hi i per tant redueix forçosament la diversió. Així com també genera situacions absurdes o injustes. Jugadors ràpids que van lents, jugadors amb menys massa muscular que d'altres que guanyen xocs físics sense problemes, jugadors baixos amb poc salt que guanyen de cap a jugadors més alts i forts, etc. No és la norma, però tampoc l'excepció, ocorre més sovint del que pot semblar. He de suposar que la raó no és manipular als jugadors per a que acabin prenent segons quines decisions ja que les coses no surten com la majoria s'esperaria al camp, sinó un desenvolupament maldestre. Sigui quina sigui la opció, l'empresa no queda gens ben parada.

Podria seguir parlant del joc sobre el camp en sí, però sento que no acabaria mai així que seguiré amb un breu comentari sobre tot el que hi al voltant. 

En resum: És lamentable. Fa vergonya.

Modes de joc completament enfocats a que infants i joves dediquin el temps a apostes encobertes amb guanys ínfims i ridículs en una espiral d'addicció que pot arribar a provocar traumes, entre d'altres patologies greus. I tot gràcies al sistema capitalisme en el que vivim actualment. Només fa ganes de vomitar. Modes de joc com el mode de carrera o d'altres continuen amb el nucli igual que al FIFA 18, amb petites adicions que al meu entendre, el tornen més feixuc enlloc de més divertit. I comentar que continua la norma de que els jugadors menors de 17 anys no són al joc i que no tots els equips compten amb llicència oficial, destacant sobretot equips italians.

Finalment dir que el primer que vaig intentar fer un cop el joc havia acabat d'instal·lar-se és jugar una temporada de [i]LaLiga[/i] amb el F.C. Barcelona d'enguany (2023/24), ja que sóc soci del club i encara hem de competir en aquesta Lliga del règim a falta de lliga Catalana oficial. Bé doncs, la meva sorpresa fou que no és possible. Només s'hi poden fer competicions (no estic parlant del mode carrera) amb les plantilles de l'any anterior, però no de l'actual. La decepció va ser gegant, però tot i així, vaig aguantar i vaig dedicar-li unes hores més. Hores avorrides i perdudes.

L'única cosa positiva que n'he tret és que m'ha fet cercar alguna alternativa vàlida i l'he trobat. Es diu Football Life 2024, una versió molt adaptada, actualitzada i millorada del Pro Evolution Soccer 2021. Una iniciativa d'un entusiasta de Palestina/Jordania que amb un grup de persones d'arreu han aconseguit oferir una gran alternativa als que ens divertim simulant el futbol de manera digital.

Thank you free weekend for giving me closure in answering whether I should consider buying this game - even in it's current 70% off discount.
The answer is NO.

The fact this game has been discounted once to 50% during the winter steam sale, and now to 70% off with a free weekend, should tell you all you need to know about how EA feel about its health - and audience about its quality.

In short: Same old, same old. 
The game is still trash.

The launcher will sometimes take 5 minutes to load, often won't load at all, and sometimes ncrash or have you looking up weird recipes on how to make it even run. I had to install the game twice just to get it to run a second time.

Performance on pc is still a disaster with huge FPS drops when you pause, when you have to take a corner kick, when there's a goal and the replay comes up, when you sneeze, when you're playing on a day that ends in 'Y'.

I only got to try the career mode and a kickoff so I'll only comment on those. Career mode has some new twists in "play styles" and other stuff I really don't know if I understand fully.
Practices got revamped so you aren't interrupted every 2 days for a practice session to just button mash "simulate" - which is amn improvement over something ooit's still amazing was even approved for the last game -- now you simply decide on team-wide or plpayer-specific ratios of performance and rest, which is in all fairness a much better take and a valid improvement. You can also do a practice session before a match for some sort of temporary boost - didn't try it though.

Players have "playstyle" modifiers, which sound good on paper. In pracftice it's... confusing? Randomly an icon will appear over their heads to signify.... I'm not sure? 

I can't really tell this ghame apart from Fifa23. Playters are still magnetically attracted to each other without touching, defending is still terrible, players are still pleased as punch to give the ball away and keep running after another player who was near them politely asked to take it from them without even a tackle, corner kicks are still meaningless and speed and finishing are the only attributes you should care for.

All in all, again: same old trash. I hope this is the last football game EA makes - theiur hearts haven't been in it for ages and we need a new team that actually wants to make a good game that comes close to "the beautiful game", not... this.

Rating: ★☆☆☆☆

As an avid fan of the FIFA series, I can't help but express my profound disappointment with FIFA 24, a game that seems to revel in mediocrity and an astonishing lack of innovation. It's disheartening to see a franchise that once set the standard for football simulation now mired in a quagmire of stagnation.

One of the most glaring issues with FIFA 24 is the blatant lack of innovation in gameplay. It's as if the developers took a time machine back to the last decade and decided that the formula from ten years ago was still cutting-edge. The game mechanics feel tired and overused, with no real attempt to introduce fresh ideas that could breathe new life into the series. It's essentially the same game on repeat, a disheartening reality for those who were hoping for progress and excitement.

The bugs and glitches in FIFA 24 are not mere hiccups; they're game-breaking nuisances that make it clear the developers prioritized a rushed release over a polished gaming experience. From players getting stuck in animation loops to bizarre physics defying the laws of football, it's as if the QA team took an extended vacation. These issues not only disrupt the flow of the game but also highlight a lack of commitment to quality control.

What's most perplexing is the disregard for fan feedback. Over the past decade, there have been countless suggestions and requests for improvements, ranging from refined career modes to enhanced AI intelligence. However, it seems as if these pleas have fallen on deaf ears, and the developers are content to ignore the loyal community that has supported the franchise for so long.

In conclusion, FIFA 24 is a prime example of a once-revered series that has lost its way. With minimal innovation, a plethora of bugs, and a refusal to listen to the voice of its community, it's difficult to recommend this game to anyone looking for a genuinely engaging football simulation experience. Save your money and stick with an older version or explore other football titles that prioritize progress and player satisfaction over a quick cash grab.

Tried this out on the free weekend. It's a nice game but I'm not sure if it's the game for me.

Graphically, it's a beautiful game with realistic looking players, fans, stadiums, etc. Top notch visual realism despite the occasional quirks like players sometimes celebrating near other players or objects and seeing their arms/legs being unnaturally bent in odd shapes or directions. That you can customize the look of your manager is a nice touch. 

Gameplay, I came into this hoping that it had a deep managerial side to the game. I just want to dictate the orders and strategies and then let the players implement the game plan as best as they can. I don't like having to control and influence players through the use of a controller, to me that defeats the purpose of being a Manager. However, that's how it defaults you. BUT, you can switch to Tactical View of the game and watch from the Manager's sideline box or switch to a spectator cam for a tv-style ease of viewing. In that you can definitely be a Manager and bark instructions to the team via keyboard commands, again I dislike using a controller as a Manager. As far as the gameplay as a player, I didn't do much of it but it seems to be somewhat intuitive though the differences between kicking and passing aren't as easy to grasp as even using the pass button on my mouse will sometimes send the ball far out of play. It takes some getting used to as far as dragging the line to tell your player which direction to run, etc. Overall, for this mode of gameplay I suppose it's fine. But I wanted to play the game as a footy manager. Controller players who will want to control the players themselves should find this mode joyful.

Depth of the game was a bit disappointing. I fully realize that there is Licensing involved as I play a fair bit of other sports manager games and they all have their quirks with feeling incomplete. This game is no exception. While I was excited to see women's leagues in the game, I was disappointed there was no Manager mode for the women. Oddly, even though I can manage men's teams in mode outside of managerial career, such as setting up a custom tournament... I was unable to do that with the women's teams. Very disappointed with that. And while I was surprised to see small footy leagues like Norway's in the game, I was shocked that Mexico's league wasn't in the game. How then can they justify having national teams for countries who don't have their leagues in the game and with no national player pool to draw from while at the same time claiming you cannot add women's management because there's not enough of a national player pool for the women? That reeks of both bias and sexism.

Overall, I think this is an alright game. It's not the best, yet it's certainly not the worst. I would say this is near the top and if improved upon could be the best. I had fun trying it out this weekend and I'm still up in the air as to whether I will buy it or wait and see if FC 25 improves upon this and adds women's management plus more international leagues and competitions for both the men and women as well as a deeper managerial career in terms of expanding on what's here with more leagues, teams and competitions. For what is here, it's still a good game. But I want total football and total control with the ability to coach any gender in any part of the world whether it's China, Chile, or Chicago. I want it all.

For players who enjoy player career modes, this is your game. From what I saw of playing around with it, it looks fantastic for that. For players who want footy manager sim game, there's enough here to give you a lot of enjoyment but you may come away feeling it's a little incomplete or lacking in depth in some areas. Still, I recommend this game because it's the closest we'll get for now to a marriage of a football manager game with phenomenal graphics.

Other reviewers are right, EA gets a lot of hate. Some of it unjustified. I'm an old-timer who remembers when EA was on 5.25" floppy discs as an Indie publisher helping Indie developers make a name for themselves. They've done a lot for the video game genre and while they've had their shortcomings over the years, I don't see it as being necessary to treat them so harshly when other companies do far, far worse. Besides, there's already enough hate and meanness in this world without my adding to it.

Peace out.

As an avid football game enthusiast, I had high hopes for EA SPORTS FC 24, but it turned out to be a massive letdown. From the get-go, the game tests your patience with its technical flaws, making the whole experience more frustrating than enjoyable.

First off, connecting to EA's servers is a nightmare. The constant errors and long waiting times just to get into the game are infuriating. It's like you're in a never-ending loop of disappointment. And if that wasn't enough, the EA launcher itself is a source of frustration, crashing every few minutes and disrupting any semblance of a smooth gaming experience.

The game is also plagued with constant notifications that pop up and interrupt the flow of play. It's like you're constantly being pulled out of the immersive world of football that you're supposed to be enjoying. But even if you manage to overlook these aspects, the gameplay itself is deeply flawed. The game runs with a frustrating lag, and it gets worse in online mode, often dropping to a dismal 20 FPS. For a fast-paced sports game, this is unacceptable.

Unfortunately, there's not a single redeeming quality in EA SPORTS FC 24 that can make up for these numerous issues. It's a huge disappointment, especially for fans of the series who expected much better. This game is a step backward in the evolution of football games, and I find it hard to recommend it to even the most die-hard football fans.

Так как играю в серию FIFA с 2010 года, что-то в игре всё таки понимаю. И не буду первопроходцем с мыслью, что EA Sports уже несколько серий кардинально нового ничего не привнесли в жанр. FC 24 это всё та же FIFA 23, которая в свою очередь FIFA 22 и так далее. Купил игру по скидке, решил, так сказать, дать 
 шанс, но нет. Я поиграл в общей сложности 40 минут и мне этого было достаточно, чтобы сделать следующие выводы: в игре есть баги, которые кочуют из серии в серию, например зависшее табло счета (казалось бы, что тут сложного исправить) и это было в первом быстром матче! Физика слегка отличается от прошлой части, но абсолютно незначительно. В Ultimate Team поиграть не удалось: при попытке открыть подарочный пак игра зависла, пришлось перезапускать игру. Второй попытки и вовсе не было, тк висел загрузочный экран с рекламой паков и всё, опять пришлось перезапустить игру. В режиме карьеры кардинальных изменений не нашел, за исключением заявленных: переработана система тренировок и тд.
Посему запросил возврат средств.
Далее моё субъективное мнение как игрока серии более 10 лет:
Мелкие баги, которые знакомы мне еще по FIFA 21, 22, 23 дают понять, что над игрой даже не заморачивались, скопировали код, поменяли составы, добавили пару "фич" и вот вам новый спортивный симулятор за цену ААА игры. При чем адекватные студии выпускают патчи, стараясь удержать свою аудиторию, дав ей понять, что им это важно. Здесь все иначе: забагованый аркадный футбол, который каждый год привносит свежую порцию ничего или просто косметические изменения, в этой вот меню переделали (стало как в PES). Я играл в карьеру и UT примерно одинаково по времени и могу сказать, что кроме собственного подогрева интереса игра никак не удерживает тебя в оффлайн режимах (уже во втором сезоне, максимум в третьем становится скучно и однообразно), мол иди играть в онлайн. А в онлайне типичный гринд: выполняй задания, бегай по 24/7, чтобы выловить паки. Но знай, что через пол года выйдет абсолютно новая версия игры, которую еще не видел киберспортивный свет и все по новой.  Пипл хавает, FUT приносит деньги, зачем стараться?
Кто-то скажет, что изменения будут заметны, если переходить с FIFA 22 или FIFA 21, но какое удовольствие играть в серию, поддержка и обслуживание которой закончится уже летом 2024 года, когда составы будут обновлять только в UT. Мне лично такое отношение говорит об одном: EA Sports уже давно не болеют футболом и им все равно: нравится нам или нет.

I recently had the pleasure of diving into the exhilarating world of EA Sports FC 24, and I must say, it's an absolute game-changer! As a devoted fan of sports simulation games, I've tried my fair share, but this one truly stands out for all the right reasons.

First and foremost, the graphics are nothing short of stunning. The attention to detail in player animations, stadium designs, and even the subtle nuances of the weather conditions make every match feel like a live, broadcasted event. EA Sports FC 24 has truly mastered the art of realism, and it adds a whole new level of immersion to the gaming experience.

The gameplay mechanics are impeccable. The controls are intuitive, allowing for seamless maneuvering on the field. Whether you're executing precise passes, pulling off jaw-dropping skill moves, or scoring that game-winning goal, the responsiveness of the controls makes every action feel natural and satisfying.

One of the standout features is the extensive customization options. EA Sports FC 24 gives players the freedom to personalize everything from team jerseys and logos to individual player attributes. It's a fantastic way to create a unique and personalized gaming experience, allowing players to truly take ownership of their virtual soccer universe.

The career mode is where EA Sports FC 24 truly shines. The depth of the mode is impressive, offering a rich narrative that goes beyond the pitch. Managing a team, making strategic decisions, and navigating through the ups and downs of a season adds a strategic layer to the game, keeping players engaged and invested in their team's success.

The multiplayer options are equally impressive, with smooth online gameplay that ensures a competitive and enjoyable experience for players around the world. Whether you're teaming up with friends or facing off against opponents, the multiplayer component adds a social dimension to the game that enhances its replay value.

In conclusion, EA Sports FC 24 has set a new standard for sports simulation games. From its breathtaking visuals to its immersive gameplay and extensive customization options, it's a must-have for any soccer enthusiast or gaming aficionado. Kudos to the developers for delivering a title that not only meets but exceeds expectations. EA Sports FC 24 is a sporting marvel that deserves every bit of praise it receives!

I played a few hours of the free weekend.  I didn't get to really experience the full game, but MyCareer was okay.  

Then I got a "Review our updated Terms" pop up when restarting the game from the EA App.  The NEXT button was broken.  Turns out it's required to login on all EA Services, so it looks like I will not be able to play any EA games for probably several days to several weeks.

The error is referencing a JavaScript Juno tosUpdate file that is experiencing "too many redirects" and the function that the Next button is relying on to progress to the actual login, is on that file.

I've played Fifa since FIFA 08 and I'm a huge fan of the series but I'm so disappointed. I can't say anything but This is the biggest piece of dogsh1+ I have ever played. I swear since FIFA 19 it's worse every year. The AI is horrible... striker being everywhere but in the box waiting for cross. When defending, I got 4 defenders in my box - literally no midfielder come for help even if there are 4 attackers in the box. The oppenent attackers are scoring the same goals as in Fifa 23... just passing the ball all over my box because no one is actually defending and my defenders are just watching and doing nothing. It's like I need to do everything myself but I can control just one player at once. Then, when I'm trying to switch, I feel like it switches to every player, but not the one who I want to.
I only play career mode and it's incredibly unrealistic when every game is like 5:3 or 4:4. The training is boring, no one actually wants to think about balancing the Energy and Sharpness. It was much better before.
Also the main menu is crap, before it was easier to find everything quickly. And the editing should be the part of menu, not just in the top left corner next to settings. When you are done editing a player, you will get to the main menu and if you want to edit a different player, you need to go back to the left corner and you must find the editing player menu again. Why don't we just stay in editing menu? 
The only thing I actually like about this game is dribbling of players like Messi or Arda Guler - I feel like I'm much more in control than before.
I really tried but I can't enjoy this game. I have played it for the last two days and I also played the beta in the summer but it's unplayable in my opinion... at least the career mode and playing against AI.

Edit: Tried it twice since the original review, I changed the difficulty from Legendary to World Class, to see what will change. I played 3 matches - won all (7:1, 6:0, 5:1). It was easier to defend because I was able to get the ball before they get to my box. The two goals I received were the same situation - 3 of my defenders were in the box, their one striker was totally lonely chilling in my box, waiting for final ball. All of my defenders were 5 metres or more from him and they did not even consider defending or getting to him. I hope that EA FC 25 will have much better AI and it will be more of a realistic game with more realistic score of a match. This can be good only for modes like Ultimate Team but not for career mode. I do not think that all of a sudden since FIFA 23 I am only good in attacking and cannot defend to save my life.

I played FIFA from 2002 to FIFA 18 and then I said enough is enough. I only tried 19, 20, 21, 22 and 23 during free weekends or free trials and each time I was glad I switched to PES. Playing co-op with friends in PES 2020 and 2021 was the most fun I had in football games for a very long time.

FIFA Pro Clubs were also pretty fun, but it was always difficult to gather a full 11 people squad, so if we didn't have enough and opponents had a full team, we didn't stand a chance.

As for what we play nowadays - eFootball finally added co-op events with matchmaking pretty recently and it's what we play the most. You can play 2v2 or 3v3 using your cards (like from FUT) and the games takes 11-12 cards from each player for 2v2 or 7-8 cards for 3v3. The party leader chooses squad and tactics from all players' cards in the lobby (Game Plan) before the start of the match, so it's really fun to play with your friends' cards.

What's also great about eFootball, all cards carryover to the next season. The game gets updated, you get new gameplay and graphics and you can still play with your favourite players. In FIFA/EA FC when you spend real money on cards, it's gone when the new game launches. In eFootball you get to keep everything (players contracts expire after 365 days, but you can extend them for GP points you get just from playing, I always have way more GP than I need).

And finally, the gameplay is way better in eFootball. I recommend turning down passing assist to PA3 (PA4 is full manual). You have more control of your passes, the ball goes more in the direction you want instead of where the assist wants it to, and it's still slightly assited, so you don't need to set the power and direction perfectly. It gets some time to get used to, but it's well worth it.

Oh, and eFootball is free, I play it since 2021 and I spent only 2€ on coins so far (I wanted specific Zieliński card from a pack and I didn't want to grind for coins then), and from free spins and other gifts or events I already have more legends than space in squad and bench (you can have 23 players in your roster - I have more legends than that for free).

This game is beyond atrocious. I have played FIFA for a long time until FIFA17. Back then it was already bad, causing me to finally give op on FIFA. Now after years I wanted to see the state of the franchise since it is free now anyway. Holy moly though. This game is insanely bad. Just to name a few things:

- It runs horribly on PC. I have a brand new high end gaming PC yet this game stutters whenever there is a cut scene or I press a button in the menus. Some audience textures don't even load.
- The AI is unbelievably bad. They pretty much do the opposite from what a football player should do. Defenders literally run out of the way for attackers.
- Corners and free kicks make no sense. They give you pretty much every instrument to perfect your shot as if you are some ballistics/physics expert with an in build super computer to calculate everything. Yet, it rarely goes where it says it would go.
- There are no tactics at all. Defenders don't hold any defensive line whatsoever and wing backs stay on the outside of their man to defend air I guess. The whole game is pretty much through balls and abusing pace because there is no defensive cohesion in any team.
- Goalkeepers might as well be ghosts. They can't save the simplest of shots. Closing down a 1vs1 with an attacker is also ridiculous. They literally make themselves as small as possible or simply step to the side.
- It doesn't feel like football at all. The pace of the match is all over the place. It can be super slow and then suddenly super fast, but none of the passes, combinations or goal scoring opportunities look anything like a football match.
- The players feel extremely sluggish. It's like you don't have any real control over them. You never know what they are gonna do.
- Every game feels the same. Players and teams don't matter. Just to test it, I played a half star Indian team, of which I can't even remember the name, against Real Madrid. Somehow my 50 rated players managed to outclass Real Madrid. They played like any 5 star rated team, and I was playing on world class difficulty even. I double checked all my settings because I could not believe how bad the AI was. The only way Real Madrid scored was because of atrocious AI defense and non-existent goalkeeping. It was incredibly boring to play.

So again: DO NOT BUY. This game should be illegal. Not just because of the predatory gambling practices in FUT, but simply because it's utter trash. If someone would offer me this game for free, I'd pay them to destroy it.

Year after year, EA, despite being one of the highest grossing video game company of all-time, you fail to actually deliver a product on release day that is reflective of its price. People are paying a premium for your games every year, and are met with some of the most lacklustre, mundane and boring features every year. Sure, you can blame us for continuing to buy the game, but the truth is, I love football. You love football. And FIFA/EA Sports FC is the only game out there that can scratch that itch. There are no viable competitors. Therefore, through our love for the beautiful game that is football, we keep buying it. And you know that, EA. That is why you refuse to actually do some hard coding in your game and add new features/improve the game.

You are too busy milking all the 12-year old FUTwhales that spend mum and dad's money on your stupid packs, which is all that ultimately matters to you in the end. You do not care that Career Mode has not been proper innovated since the dawn of Jesus Christ, or that Pro Clubs has so much untapped potential. All that matters to you, is FUT, and the whales that keep splashing thousands upon thousands every year, only for all of their players, items, to be obsolete the following iteration of FIFA/EAFC.

I would also like to point out that, despite us paying the same amount, the level of disrespect you have continuously shown us PC players is unforgivable. Not just this year, but every other year. Do not think we have forgot about the absolute disaster of a release that was FIFA 21, FIFA 22 and FIFA 23. If you are lucky enough to even launch the game, you are most likely met with terrible FPS, choppy animations, bugged out player models, and honestly, the list is endless if I wanted it to be. Speaking of lists, I am going to provide one with all of the bugs that I encountered in my first few hours of game-play.

→ Choppy animations, frames drop and becomes an eye-sore to watch.
→ Commentary does not work on launch. There is 0 commentary.
→ Player models, the hair, bugs out when it is rainy and foggy. Becomes pixelated.
→ Can not connect to the internet (whatever this means).
→ Controllers not working properly.
→ Game keeps minimising on PC.
→ The game is not opening and launching for so many players.
→ Can not sack coaches in Career Mode, it just freezes.
→ Objectives not counting.
→ Not getting XP when completing objectives.
→ The game freezes on the EA FC logo.
→ Stuck in half-time animation.
→ Game-play stutter.
→ Overall TERRIBLE performance even on high-end hardware.
→ Anti-cheat error message.
→ Media questions still make 0 sense.
→ Same animations for media interviews and transfers.
→ Same animations for injuries, etc. 0 innovation and creativity here.
→ Menu in FUT will freeze and you have to close the game and launch it again.
→ If you navigate the menu too quickly, it messes up and goes all over your screen.

Again, like mentioned, this list could be as long as you want it to be. The point is, you are incompetent EA, and you are ESPECIALLY incompetent when it comes to creating a proper PC port. But of course, because you know we love football and we simply have no other alternatives, you can keep getting away with this. I am an idiot for playing this game and "enabling it" and I know I am, but that is not going to stop me from speaking out about the disgrace of a company you run.

Also, why on Earth would you remove players walking out onto the pitch and lining up before a game? What went on in your heads over there at EA when you thought, hmm, let us replace this key part of immersion building and realism and replace it with a few stupid cutscenes then immediately throw you into the game where everyone is already on the pitch ready to go. What about Champions League nights, important finals, etc? There is no immersion anymore. You do not get to watch your team walk out, line up, with the anthem roaring in the background, your players lined up and ready to battle it out... it just sends you straight into action. This is SO stupid. As a Career Mode enjoyer (shocking, I know right, cause who still willingly plays this neglected mode?) this totally kills off getting any sort of feeling towards your games, especially big ones. Mind-boggling decision. Begs the question, in typical EA fashion, which iteration of EA FC will you bring back and market as a "brand new, immersive feature"?

Sadly there are a fair few bugs on the PC/Steam version:
1. Laggy/Jumpy cutscenes/celebrations
2. Training commands keep repeating during practice sessions when they have told you several times before.
3. Running animations in character creation look terrible with skeleton issues.
4. Mouse and controller constantly fight each other on menus. Even when you move the mouse off screen when you finish a game or open a menu it resets back to the centre of the screen to begin a fight again.
5. Controller inputs on the bumpers and triggers tend to be hit an miss as to whether they get recognised.

Edit:
More bugs found after a longer play and one that makes Ultimate team completely unplayable. Unsure what causes it but whenever I skip the cutscene in ultimate team the pre-game scenes remain on pitch and players run around doing the T pose and unable to touch the ball.

So i played some Fifa games in the past like the original Fifa Street, 09, 12, 13 and 14. So compared to those i think gameplay (when it's good) is better. But, there are many faults with this game. Random connection losses not due to my internet, UT is crashing most of the time when trying to buy players in the club or SBC Club section, menus being slow and way slower than normal at times, the gameplay is very inconsistent a lot of the time with players being slow at shooting or passing the ball and some passes not hitting at all (This is a reoccurring issue from the previous installments from what I've heard 20, 21, 22 and 23). If you can get over those issues it can be a great game, but most of the time it kinda sucks the joy out of it. Would i recommend this game? Maybe, if you're trying to play the game competitively while taking it very seriously, i wouldn't recommend it, that will just end up in you breaking your equipment which is not a very good economical decision considering the game is already 70€ (which is kinda overpriced for what you get). For casuals? I would say you can have some joy in this game, but it has definitely lost it's shine over the years and has become more and more pay to win since last i played which was Fifa 14. I hope they redo the spaghetti code this game runs on for the coming installments in the series, if not i wouldn't say it's worth copping unless you have a pack opening addiction.

First off, I'm a FUT player, so I think I can call myself a "non-casual" player unlike the people that only play seasons or career mode, which I would consider "casual." I play rivals every week and weekend league every weekend for the first couple months after release.

There are things that I absolutely love about this game. When gameplay is good, it's really fun. But, EA hasn't optimized this game for PC and it can be very jittery and unresponsive, which seems like it's occurring more and more. FYI, I play this on a ~$2000 custom built PC, so it should run VERY well and it just doesn't. 

Ping isn't respective of what actually happens in game. When you're loading in, it'll tell you that you have 20 ms ping and then once you get into the game your ping will spike to 50+. 

I love soccer (Liverpool fan), and I log onto this game everyday just to see what SBCs there are and to play a couple games. However, I find myself not wanting to play, or just logging on and logging back off. I would love a soccer game that just focuses on good gameplay, and EA has missed that this year.

The game has the exact bugs from Fifa 23 and even more.

The UT has 4 game modes (Division Rivals/Squad Battles/Fut Champions/FutDraft) and every game mode feels different, the players move differently, the players seem to have different stats, u have to learn 4 different games to play it.

Most of the players have fake stats that doesn't apply in game, for example, every CB with 80+ pace can easily catch a striker with 99 pace.

Every shot from outside the big area is goal, or at least 95% of the shots.

The women are overpowered, most of them have stats better then the big players that we now nowadays.

The objectives are always bugged, saying that u have completed some, and then u go redeem it still stays u have to redeem.

A lot of times the images in the player cards are bugged, and appears the card without the player, or with 2 players.

Once icons were like an achievement, something that make us feel good and powerful because it was hard to get them, now there's like 20+ SBCs of icons, most of them easy to complete and they give tons of them also in the season pass so icons now are like normal players.

There's one specific graphics definition (the one specific to the hair) that causes you to lose a lot of fps in cut scenes, like you are playing in 144+ fps and drop to 20.

The gameplay is a disgrace, with bugs every match and the AI is just terrible and stupid most of the times and make it so that you suffer goals in the most ridiculous possible way.

The introduction of playstyles and evolutions are fantastic.  The introduction of women's players into FUT is wonderful.

But the online play modes are currently awful. The midfield is horribly congested and the AI autopress is hilariously overpowered.  If you try and play tiki taka football in a way that has been possible for the last 10 or so FIFA games, this time you'll struggle to put more than two passes together before the ball is intercepted by an opposition attacker with low defensive stats.

There was a period following a patch in December where the gameplay was much better but things seem to have regressed badly by early January.  This has been deflating because it suggests the autopressing gameplay is an intentional design decision by EA - rather than a clumsy attempt to counter negative park the bus online play.  If this is the case, I think this might be the last FIFA/FC game I play in a while.

For reference, I am running this game on a high end gaming PC.
I have played almost every FIFA since FIFA 96, and it's no secret that EA do very little to change the games each year, but this year's edition really takes the price for low effort from EA. It really does feel like this is a BETA edition and we are still waiting for EA to release the finished game. EA football fans must have becomes accustomed to half finished games, otherwise there would have been an uproar. CDPR received so much negative press for their disastrous Cyberpunk 2077 release, a game they then spent a long time fixing to give the fans what they initially promised. Trust me when I say, this launch is much worse than CDPR's, and it has already been four months and no sign of EA trying to fix anything. I also find it an insult to the fans that a game released in 2023 is adapted to run on a severely outdated PS4, it shows how little effort EA have put into making it the best game possible, they just want to make money from it. 
They have as in previous versions, taken the predecessor (FIFA 23) and edited it, which should have been fine as FIFA 23 is a decent game, but the decisions they have made along the way are terrible. Everything seems like it's geared towards the features where they can make money from microtransactions, and the features that made the game so popular over the years have been neglected. Manager career mode is plagued with bugs, features that don't work, other features that instantly forces CTDs. Player career mode is really lackluster as your CPU controlled team mates act the same as players you don't control while you play the whole team, meaning the defenders sort of just run along with the attackers but don't actually try to take the ball away from them. There is no possible way either of these features passed any sort of testing phase in the EA developing office.
There are a ton of other issues as well that shouldn't have passed any testing, the pitch weather and lighting can completely change as the ball goes out for a throw-in or goal kick. Giant blocky shadows appear and disappear during game play, I've had random players freeze in place while the game still moves on and the other 21 players move just fine.
If all the issues and unfinished game play wasn't enough, there are also really odd additions. The lighting in the player creation screen now comes from the side rather than head on, so you can only clearly see half the player's face, another feature that shouldn't have passed any testing. As usual, the game is designed to simulate a TV broadcast, so why did they have the referees hand out cards in first person? You go from playing in third person to suddenly see the view from the referee's eyes. why? The game is full of these odd decisions. 
I highly recommend you stick to FIFA 23 or football games not made by EA. I would say wait until EA fix this mess but I really don't think they have any plans to. Very sad to see such a large gaming company release such an unfinished game.

I've had a couple of hours of this brown gem of the gaming industry...

Issues experienced in ONLY 6 hours of playtime, which makes me stop playing it:

7 CRASHES:
- 4 crashes of the anti-cheat with "117" error code in the middle of a Rivals match, assuming that I am suspiciously cheating when I never dare to cheat, as I've spent a lot of money, probably over £1000.- on my games and skins on Steam and EA both.
- 3 random crashes without any sign or error code; the game just simply disappeared into the fog.

RANDOM CONTROLLER DISCONNECTS (HAPPENED 3 TIMES):
- While I was able to use my controllers Xbox button (the big X with the light) and inputs worked outside of the game, the game showed me a message that said my input device is disconnected and I had to restart the game to make it work properly again.

GAME IS STUCK:
- Once I was in the menu, the game did not respond to any of my input except the one that opens my friend list, the right trigger.
So, I was not able to navigate in the menu, neither with my keyboard, so I had to ALT+F4.
Sometimes, the game also stuck on start-up; FC24 image comes out, but the game would not launch at all.

STORE NOT WORKING:
- I also experienced some problems in the store.
I am not sure if it is a network issue-related problem or if it was a local issue, but I was unable to order any packs until I restarted the game.

PERFORMANCE ISSUES:
- I am playing on a high-end PC (Ryzen 9 3900X, RX 7900 XTX, 48 GB RAM, bunch of m2 SSDs), and I had a lot of FPS issues and stuck/stuttering, especially when I had the cinematic after a goal, missed chance, or the referee giving a card cinematic.

I have a couple of hundred hours in FIFA/FC or whatever it is called, but what I can see now is that this game is going down a slide and getting worse and worse every year and draining funds from the players, but don't misunderstand me, I also bought the game AGAIN, even after a decision when I said I will not buy it again, so there is no lazy/get used to it company without a horde of sheep to burn their money.
My personal peak was the 21, and the 22 was alright of the latest EA football games, but it was also very annoying sometimes with the bugs and the overpowered players like Fekir, Ben Yeder, etc. However, 2007 was the one I was really in love with.

I believe that most players would be happy if these problems were finally fixed, and we could play with a smooth and issue-less game.

I know I did not even talk about my personal experience, which was alright.
The game, on its own, is fine-ish.
Players are extremely slow in my scenario and I cannot enjoy the defending, which is barely possible most of the time as the players are running everywhere and when they have to act with a slide or step in or anything, it is really hard to control them in the right way.
The game flows well, by the way; overall mood is okay; sometimes it feels like you are playing football.

Personal best thing during game-play:
Hyper-motion stuff, nice analytics and visual invention give a lot to the game.
I like the half-time animations with those walk-in to the changing room and warm-up animations.

Personal worst thing during game-play:
Power shot Zoom in makes defence even harder.

I would recommend buying this game because I want a better FIFA/FC again, and I know it requires a lot of funds, even more than what we've paid already with the packs and for the games. Where do I start here? I have been playing fifa games on and off for many years.
This game has quite some things to offer that would make it a good game. However, there are way too many flaws that hinder this from being a good game. At the end of the day, gamplay is the most important aspect (or should be...!) - but it seems EA is more concentrating on flooding the community with outside gameplay content, instead of working on the core issues of this game.
No. 1 and the most important for all plattforms:
Inconsistend gameplay - games where players turning luck trucks, take extra unnecessary touches, despite passing / shooting / skill move / direction change has been triggered for ages. This may all come down to lag compensation for me, as I have a stable good internet connection with about 20 ms latency to ea servers. But whatever the cause of this may be, this makes this game not enjoyable, even frustrating at times. If it is lag compensation, even worse, as this would mean people with good internet connections get punished (and put at a disadvantage) for the sake of people with lousy connections.
No 2. especially for PC users:
Awefully optimized for PC!! Same problems that constisted already in previous versions persist. Obviously EA is not interested in spending any resources into making this game decently playable on pc. I am running on a 7600X with a 6950 XT GPU and yet my graphics card is taken to to limit when just entering the menu. If you have set up 120ish fps or higher, the game runs at the same fps in the menus, let alone you unlimited the fps, which bring the FPS to 400 / 500 fps in the menus with 100% GPU utilization. Thing is, the menus are even harsher on the gpu as the actual gameplay is, which is beyond ridiculous. Then there is the mouse bug that hasn't been fixed from previous alterations, where you cant click buttons in the menu, as your mouse reappears in the middle of the screen occasionally.
No 3.: obviously blatant pay to win mechanics, nothing new here. This is only half way to blame on EA, the other half goes out to people spending money for digital content on this game. This is naturally everyone's decision, however to me this is beyond insanity.
No 4.: Bugs & Missing convenience
Just a few examples of what I mean by that:
- When you have duplicates, you can't buy players on the market via the smartphone app, ingame on the pc that is no problem.
- Simply missing obvious helpful options, such as limit player search to a certain ratio rating (e.g. 75 - 80) or
a function to select all you duplicates for a SBC, other than remembering each and everyone of them and searching and selecting them one by one. I can't understand why such easy functions are not in the game.
- Various crashes when tapping out of the game
- Game sometimes just freezes and crashes on the transfer market

This is written by a casual player, winning some games and losing some. For me it is not about just about winning and losing, but the experience in the process.

Hope this helps some people out making a decision on whether or not they should buy this game (let alone invest money for digital content).

Cheers

Edit: Completely forgot to mention the stutter occuring when the game switches from ingame to cutscences, whether you have set the cutscences to half frame rate or full frame rate. No matter which settings I choose in the game or in the graphic cards driver, this problem persisted.

The game mostly remains a repeat of Fifa 23, carrying over many of the same features masked in newly designed user menus (slightly more confusing to navigate). The gameplay (online multiplayer, Ultimate Team) is fast paced, often times reaching scorelines of 5+ goals, and can seem inconsistent at times in regards to the matchups with other players. The addition of in-game playstyles also adds to this inconsistency, where a specialist trait can guarantee a free kick, long power shot, or other type of goal. On a notable aspect, animations are fluid and the motion capture has been done very nicely in the new Hypermotion V segment. While some will enjoy the smooth movement, seasoned players may find left stick control lacking without the use of the close dribble playstyle.

Overall, its a football video game which most will be familiar with over other offerings, and even if "Fifa" isn't in the title anymore, it remains a chill (but bug filled) title that you can grind for hours, or pickup once in a while.

TLDR; Build team of players, run around with ball, put ball in net, repeat.

So I've waited a fair time to review this product, let me start off by saying that I have enjoyed FIFA for many years, with my first title being FIFA 13. 

I'd not recommend this game to anyone on PC. The reasoning behind this due to the below issues:

- Cursor glitch: physical cursor displays on screen when using a controller. You can disconnect your mouse and it'll still appear on the screen, even  mid game play.

- Poor servers: The servers for AU players are horrendous. I am running a wired connecting from my router to PC and the game states I have 24ms ping at all times. However, this is not the case... I have used a tool on EA's own website to test my connection to the servers and the result came back at over 300ms ping. 

- Game play is one dimensional: Meta has truly ruined this game. You simply cannot enjoy the game by using non-meta players. For instance, in FIFA 13/14, you could use a silver Brazilian team and be genuinely competitive against a fairly stacked team... this is what made the game fun.

- Input delay: The game on PC experiences a heavy input delay, whether the gameplay is good or bad. I do not believe a user should have to search far and wide to find the best settings in a game to experience the game at it's full capacity. Consumers pay for a finished product, not a product that is not optimised for a PC gaming experience.

Furthermore, not to mention the scripted moments within the game. In Ultimate Team, there's dynamic difficulty adjustment, which ensures your players are performing worse than their base states would suggest. There's no need for this in a Football simulator. Not only does it frustrate all players at all levels, it also disrupts the integrity of the game (not that there is much to begin with). 

There are moments when I do enjoy the game, however, these are all enjoyed with playing against my mates.

Please avoid this game.

Red lentil, chickpea & chilli soup

if you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding Red lentil, chickpea & chilli soup recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients

2 tsp cumin seeds
large pinch chilli flakes
1 tbsp olive oil
1 red onion, chopped
140g red split lentils
850ml vegetable stock or water
400g can tomatoes, whole or chopped
4 tbsp 0% Greek yogurt, to serve

200g can chickpeas or ½ a can, drained and rinsed (freeze leftovers)

small bunch coriander, roughly chopped (save a few leaves, to serve)

Directions

STEP 1
Heat a large saucepan and dry-fry 2 tsp cumin seeds and a large pinch of chilli flakes for 1 min, or until they start to jump around the pan and release their aromas.

STEP 2
Add 1 tbsp olive oil and 1 chopped red onion, and cook for 5 mins.

STEP 3
Stir in 140g red split lentils, 850ml vegetable stock or water and a 400g can tomatoes, then bring to the boil. Simmer for 15 mins until the lentils have softened.

STEP 4
Whizz the soup with a stick blender or in a food processor until it is a rough purée, pour back into the pan and add a 200g can drained and rinsed chickpeas.

STEP 5
Heat gently, season well and stir in a small bunch of chopped coriander, reserving a few leaves to serve. Finish with 4 tbsp 0% Greek yogurt and extra coriander leaves.

Sadly addicted. Please take this as a warning and a strong recommendation to not get this game. This has more issues than the user interface just outright breaking from time to time or the game deciding your controller isn't plugged in despite being able to use it in the interface and now it's time to use your KB+M in games all of a sudden. I suppose it is marginally better than the game constantly blue screening like last year. There's a lot of weird in this game, and that's before we've got to the show that is an actual match.

This game doesn't feel like football. Your defenders have a knack of just switching off and not defending. Your attackers regularly don't use their apparent stats and start running when you have opportunities to break out and just idly trot instead. Playing online and offline is a joke in and of itself. People in the community say this is just skill issues. But then again anybody who isn't using 'skill issue' ironically is not to be listened to anyway.

Shooting is all dice rolls, the game turns into a quagmire whenever anybody applies any pressure tactics. Playing online can feel okay one moment and then absolutely dreadful the next. I've been an avid fan of the FIFA series for years, eagerly anticipating each new release with the hope of an improved gaming experience. However, EA FC 2024 has left me utterly disappointed and questioning the direction in which the franchise is heading. Strap yourselves in for a scathing review because this game is an absolute dumpster fire.

Let's kick things off with the most glaring issue - frame drops. Yes, you heard it right. In 2024, with cutting-edge hardware at my disposal, I still find myself encountering infuriating frame drops during crucial moments, such as corners and goal celebrations. It's almost as if the game is punishing me for successfully earning a set-piece or scoring a brilliant goal. These frame drops not only ruin the immersive experience but also affect gameplay, making it impossible to time your actions correctly. Imagine trying to defend a corner or relish a well-deserved goal only to be thwarted by a sudden lag spike – it's beyond frustrating.

But that's not all. The game mechanics feel clunkier than ever before. Player movements are sluggish, ball physics are wonky, and the once-fluid gameplay has been replaced by an awkward and disjointed mess. It's like controlling a group of players who have never seen a soccer ball in their lives. EA FC 2024 takes a step backward in terms of playability, leaving me yearning for the smooth, responsive controls of its predecessors.

The graphics, touted as a selling point, are nothing more than a facade. Sure, the players might look more realistic, but what's the point when the overall presentation is marred by graphical glitches and awkward animations? I've witnessed players contorting into unnatural positions, goalkeepers performing acrobatics that defy the laws of physics, and ball trajectories that defy logic. It's as if the developers prioritized realism in appearance over actual gameplay quality.

In conclusion, EA FC 2024 is a disappointment of epic proportions. It's a regression from previous installments, plagued by frame drops, clunky gameplay, and an overwhelming emphasis on microtransactions. If you're a true fan of the FIFA series, do yourself a favor and stick to the earlier, more enjoyable editions. EA, it's time to step up your game or risk alienating the very community that has supported you for so long.

EA SPORTS FC™ 24 is an absolute trainwreck of a game, plagued by two major issues that make it nothing short of a complete waste of time and money.

First off, let's talk about the fact that the game cannot even start properly. It's astonishing how a game released by a major publisher like EA can have such fundamental issues. Time and time again, I've tried to launch the game, only to be met with endless loading screens, crashes, and game-breaking bugs. It's like EA didn't bother with any quality control whatsoever. It's infuriating to spend your hard-earned money on a product that can't even perform its most basic function – starting the game!

But it doesn't end there. EA, true to their reputation, has also managed to mess up the microtransactions in the game. You'd think they would have perfected this aspect by now, but no. The inability to purchase Points, the in-game currency necessary for any sort of progress, is laughably frustrating. I've tried multiple times to give them even more of my money in exchange for Points, but the game just won't let me. It's as if they don't want my money or care about their paying customers.

In summary, EA SPORTS FC™ 24 is a total disaster of a game. The fact that it can't even start reliably and the broken microtransactions are just the tip of the iceberg. This game is a prime example of everything that's wrong with the gaming industry – releasing unfinished, broken products and then trying to squeeze every last dollar out of players. Save your money and your sanity and stay far away from this mess of a game. EA should be ashamed of themselves for releasing this travesty.

Well where to start with this. Its the weakest game EA made about football in the now ended FIFA series that was legendary a while back. 

First of all my review is for the single player of the game as this is all i play but some points may pass over to multiplayer. 

Its been months since it released yet there are so many bugs in it you might as well consider this game early access. I had players play all games in the season and they submit a transfer request for not playing enough. I had a player ask me to take him off for the next game because he was tired (He was) and when i did just that he got angry and wanted to be transferred. The board objectives make no sense sometimes like they want me to raise the average age of the team but also sign young players. Also there are numerous graphical glitches and they show in every game like clipping and pixelated parts of the textures while the rest of them are fine. 

Most of the time i don't feel like i am controlling the players. I can literally feel fighting with the player i am controlling to force him to do what i need. They added thousands of new animations but i feel like now i am getting stuck in an animation for every movement i do causing lots of issues. 
Defending is horrid. All matches i play live end with outlandish scores like 5-6 or 8-6. Every time i concede a goal it feels like i am conceding the same 3 or 4 goals. I also score a lot of goals but they are the same over and over. The game no longer allows variation just grab a fast winger and score. Hat tricks all over the place and no matter what defender i use its the same. The rival team players become like gods at times making it impossible to defend them like powering through tackles and not being fazed and getting insane speed bonuses with the ball and off the ball. I had cases where a player would just get tackled multiple times without loosing the ball at all. I can hear my tackle making contact but he just clips through. Even when i score it feels like i am cheesing the game. Scoring goals is fun but when you score so much they loose their value.

I recently had the misfortune of diving into the latest instalment of EA FC24, and to say I was disappointed would be an understatement. Year after year, EA seems to be stuck in a repetitive loop, churning out virtually the same game with minimal improvements, and the lack of optimisation only adds insult to injury.

First and foremost, the most glaring issue with EA FC24 is the sheer lack of innovation. It's as if the developers are content with recycling the same gameplay mechanics, graphics, and features from the previous iterations. The promised improvements are barely noticeable, and any attempts at freshening up the gaming experience fall flat. It's disheartening to see a franchise with such potential stagnate in this way.

Optimization is another thorn in the side of EA FC24. Despite the leaps in technology and the capabilities of modern gaming systems, the game still suffers from poor optimization. Load times are excruciatingly long, and the frame rates drop consistently, even on high-end hardware. It's baffling how a major gaming company like EA fails to address fundamental performance issues, leaving players frustrated and wondering if their investment was worth it.

Moreover, the in-game microtransactions continue to be a sore point for many players. While EA claims to provide a fair balance between in-game purchases and rewarding gameplay, the reality is far from it. The game often feels like a thinly veiled cash grab, with players being bombarded by prompts to spend real money for virtual items. This relentless push for additional revenue detracts from the overall gaming experience and leaves a bitter taste in the mouths of those who hoped for a more player-centric approach.

In conclusion, EA FC24 is a prime example of a once-great franchise resting on its laurels. The lack of innovation, poor optimisation, and the relentless pursuit of microtransaction profits make it difficult to recommend this game to anyone looking for a fresh and enjoyable gaming experience. Until EA addresses these fundamental issues, it seems like the glory days of the franchise are long gone.

FIFA 24, along with its associated EA FC 24 features, promised to be a game-changing experience for avid football gaming enthusiasts. However, as the dust settles and the excitement wanes, it becomes evident that the reality falls short of expectations. This honest review aims to shed light on the shortcomings and disappointments that plague this edition of the popular franchise.

Gameplay Mechanics:

One of the fundamental aspects of any sports game is the gameplay mechanics, and unfortunately, FIFA 24 leaves much to be desired in this department. The touted improvements in player movements and ball physics often feel inconsistent and glitch-ridden. Players seem to defy the laws of physics, and the ball behaves erratically, leading to frustrating and unrealistic gameplay experiences.

Graphics and Presentation:

While FIFA has always prided itself on its realistic graphics, the same cannot be said for FIFA 24. The graphics seem dated and fail to showcase a significant leap forward from its predecessors. Character models lack the level of detail expected in a game of this caliber, and the stadiums, while recognizable, lack the immersive atmosphere that should accompany a top-tier football simulation.

Career Mode and EA FC 24 Features:

One of the biggest letdowns is the stagnation in Career Mode and EA FC 24 features. Despite promises of innovation and enhancements, these modes remain virtually unchanged, with minor tweaks that do little to elevate the overall gaming experience. The lack of meaningful updates in career progression, transfers, and managerial interactions leaves long-time players feeling neglected.

Microtransactions and Loot Boxes:

EA's persistent reliance on microtransactions and loot boxes continues to be a sore point for players. The pay-to-win elements undermine the concept of fair competition and turn what should be a skill-based game into a money-driven enterprise. The frustration of constantly facing opponents with superior teams due to in-game purchases is a turnoff for many players.

Server Issues and Connectivity:

No honest review of FIFA 24 would be complete without addressing the persistent server issues and connectivity problems. Frequent disconnections, lag, and matchmaking troubles have plagued the gaming experience, making it difficult for players to enjoy a smooth and uninterrupted session. This is particularly frustrating given the game's online multiplayer emphasis.

Conclusion:

In conclusion, FIFA 24 and its associated EA FC 24 features fall short of the high standards set by its predecessors. From lackluster gameplay mechanics to unimpressive graphics, stagnant career modes, and pervasive microtransactions, the game fails to deliver the revolutionary experience it promised. While the love for football and the franchise's legacy might keep some players engaged, it's hard to overlook the numerous disappointments that hinder the overall enjoyment of FIFA 24.

I've played Fifa almost every year and I also play FUT. I like the feel of dopamine when that final score weigh in your favour. Some wins in Div. 1 / Elite can be a nice dopamine boost before a good night sleep.

But some things have changed with FC24. For FUT, at least (or most, since it's what I mainly play). 

This game has taken the ever-existing "pay-to-win" concept to a whole new level. I guess it's really the time to reap that gambling addiction from some mediocre try-hards. What do I mean by that?

Two letters and two-words: "AI" and "brain-dead".

These two complement each other really well. Why do you even need to "get good" when the AI will do all the defending for you? You just need to fork out some money for that high rated icons and maybe VVD and you're set to auto-pilot to victory.

If you were tackled by your opponent, if you have those meta players (read: money) the ball will magically bounce back to your player's feet. Just dribble along the sideline and then the back line and pass to the player waiting in the middle of the penalty box. As simple as that.

Most of the time, you'll experience the brain-dead-over crowding. Tactics? Pffftt... Get lost! 9 out of 10 times, you'll meet with great teams but totally boring generic, non-creative, sweaty-rat-style type of gameplay. Losing to a better player is acceptable and I love it. But 9 times out of 10, you'll lose to crappy things like rebounds, finesses, sweats. 

If you're a sucka like me who can't quit the dopamine rush, then too bad. You'll be trapped in the downward spiral of cannot   putting this game down. Even though it consume your precious time, (and some times, your precious soul).

So, play at your own risk. 😂

The game is scripted. Especially online. The reason is simple, it is called "intermittent reinforcement" (look it up, it is the basis of gambling). Basically you alternate, at random intervals, moments when your players are gods, to others when they look like they just got out of an "all you can drink" night. All to create addiction and keep you hooked on the game.
I already know that some people might say "you're just bad" and  I never said I was a phenomenon. But can you explain to me, then, why the same players, in the same division, go from being completely retarded by missing defensive exits, trivial passes and so on, to being perfect machines (and vice versa) within a few games?
It makes no sense. EA has ruined soccer games. Hopefully someone else will come along and sweep this crap away.

As we get another year of pure focus into ultimate team, EA are consistent on making game play updates that progressively lead to the decline in sales and player count in this game. Every year the game feels sub-par at launch, but 2-3 months into the game cycle after 1 or 2 gameplay updates, the game feels awful and non-rewarding to play. Even in ultimate team, their most anticipated addition with evolution players are now being placed behind pay walls. All they care about is sucking more money from the consumer rather than retaining their true and authentic fan base. Again, I find myself stuck building concept squads for hours in ultimate team menus, to eventually not even play due to the horrid and frustrating gameplay.
