If you are someone who wants to enjoy pvp matches and score goals that make real world footballing sense, please don't waste your hard earned money. Been a fan since FIFA17 and this is the most disappointed i've ever been. Expect the same meta every pvp game- Crowded unplayable midfield and full depth press from opponent to boot, run up along the bi-line cutback and trivela/finesse merchant it towards goal. It's not an issue of skill in learning the mechanics, but rather the disgust in seeing unrealistic tactical gameplay and the inability to play the game as i see fit.

The handicap system in Ultimate team is the worse I've seen on a Fifa game. If you score 2 goals before the 20th minute of the game, you're likely going to draw or lose the game. It happens way too many times. Also you get loan player objectives, but if you start the game and your opponent just consede, you loose a game for that loan player and you don't get the win. Stupidest thing I've ever seen on a football simulator. Another thing related to this, is that if you're losing and oppo draws the game and consedes right away out of spite, you're getting nothing.. There's no need to spend money in game if you're average, as the packs are easier than last years to earn. Other than this, it's a OK game I guess.

The game is like every game before it, it's evidently flawed. While it claims to be a football simulator, it's more of an exploit simulator. If you don't conform to the prevailing trends in team composition and player abilities, centered around what is exploitable, you'll find yourself unable to compete against those who do, and you will lose. Learning and executing exploits becomes a necessity, and while there are numerous tutorial videos available, succumbing to this approach can ruin the overall gaming experience. The game's current form, and as per discussions with other players, past and possibly future iterations, is highly exploitable. Consequently, you'll witness only three types of goals in this so-called football simulator. While you may score and witness hundreds of goals like these, the game's rigidity to these play styles and game-breaking mechanics eradicates the sense of being immersed in a football simulator. To wrap it up. Frankly, I anticipated much more from the purported best-in-industry and expensive game. This disappointment isn't solely based on the gameplay; it extends to actual bugs involving matchmaking, glitched menus, automatic configuration reverting, uniform malfunctions, a community rife with sore losers resorting to excessive slide tackles and leaving matches when behind, glitched animations, inexplicable computer decisions, alleged handicapping of matches, and other issues that my friends and I endured to play this game. In summary, and being entirely candid, I strongly advise against subjecting yourself to this experience. I mainly play career mode now and while it’s more enjoyable they didn't really add anything new this time around or ever to be honest. If you do get the game I suggest sticking to career mode if you want to keep your sanity intact. That’s the only way I’ve been able to enjoy it. But if you liked the previous games you'll enjoy this one too.
Horrible support from developers. Can't play half the game modes. Don't waste your money and time.

- Click "Play". Wait for Steam to connect EA Play, and wait for EA Play to authorize Steam. Click to continue, choose a profile, select the game mode, and stare at the new microtransaction opportunities. There was an error connecting to the EA servers. Repeat the process and congratulations on wasting 10 minutes getting the game started.

- Finally get into Ultimate Team. A couple of notifications on the objectives tab. Spend another 10 minutes trying to figure out which completed objectives you did not claim. Turns out it was a visual bug that hasn't been fixed for the past X months.

- Check if there are new Evolutions. Pay 150k coins for an evolution to increase the overall rating of your player by 2 if you complete 40 games played. 

- Open the packs given to you for being a loyal customer who wastes time and money in exchange for frustration. Feed your inner gambler.

- Finally have a squad full of players that you wished for even before you purchased the game. Make the tactics that fit your and the squad's playstyle. Get into Rivals and lose matches consecutively.

- Realize you conceded the same goals over and over again and all the teams you played against have players chosen from a pool of 20-30 useful players. 

- Check online what is wrong with your team. Basically everything. There are two working formations with two custom tactics variations and none of your players are part of the meta so they are trash no matter how good or unique they are in real life.

- Become what you hate and mimic thousands of other people playing the same way to compete with them. Spend time and money to catch up with them. Still be mediocre because you cannot keep up with the pace of the game and stick to the same scoring pattern over and over again or cannot accomplish Mortal Kombatlike skill moves where you need to click both L3 and R3 with your eyeballs then do a backflip and sit on a cucumber to accomplish el crochetta de la boomshakalaka move to beat the new Dark Souls boss Virgil van Dijk.

- Get frustrated, try squad battles. Semi-pro, pro, and world class difficulties are like playing against an afk player. Go above that and you wont be able to touch the ball against a 60 overall team that wastes time and mimics the same cancerous gameplay you experienced in the Rivals.

- Try pro clubs with your friends. Get frustrated together.

- Try career mode. Becoming a goalkeeper sounds fun so you become one and sign for a fourth-division team. Get selected for the team. The manager expects 8.0 overall performance from you. Wait in position for the whole game since the other team is not capable of shooting once in 90 minutes which means you did not make a single save and your rating drops to 5.0 from the default 6.0. Get benched in the next game because you did not score a hat trick as a goalkeeper to get 8.0 rating. Leave immediately.

I want to enjoy this game, I really do. There are a lot of improvements made but still a few months after release, nothing has changed. Just some background, I've been playing 'EA FC' (Formerly FIFA) for a few years now - since FIFA 22 and this one has no notable improvements, in fact I'd say it is worse than its predecessors.

What I like: 
-Visually it's stunning, I must say the graphics are a major upgrade and I love how the game looks
-The UI, I love the new in game UI for the premier league and la liga etc. though not so sure about the title screen UI, feels a bit clunky to me.
-Dynamic animations. I love the new dynamic change room animations etc, but in a game as big as the Champions League final I don't want to see a quick few cut scenes, I want longer animations that immerse me and get me excited for the game.

What I don't like:
-The new referee AI is terrible. I usually play career modes and it is red cards galore for what are fairly tame fouls. Moreover, don't even get me started on advantage. Recently in a round of 8 UCL match my player was tackled and the ref continued to play advantage after a pass was intercepted from the person that was tackled, they scored from that and we lost 1-0. 
-No innovations at all. No VAR. Nothing. to be honest it's all the same and that frustrates me to all hell. It's not even the thought of VAR checking decisions - it's the tension laden moments just before a penalty is awarded etc.. Of course if should be skip able but it's the thought that counts.
-No focus on anything other than FUT. The player agent sucks. Yes in some cases its good, but I can't get into the transfer market and see what clubs want me etc.. Manager career still has common sense issues like being unable to cancel a players transfer request even though they are asking for a contract renewal and other issues. All of EA's effort goes into the cash cow - FUT, which for your average player is a total sweat fest.

Those are a few issues, but unless something changes next year, I certainly will not be buying the next game.

My experience with FC 24 on my mid-high end PC was far from satisfactory. The game's performance was consistently disappointing, struggling to maintain a decent frame rate and delivering choppy, lag-filled graphics. On top of that, frequent disconnections from the server disrupted my gameplay, leaving me frustrated and disconnected from the intended experience.

The gameplay itself left much to be desired, with clunky and unresponsive mechanics that hindered the enjoyment of action sequences. Controls lacked the expected precision, leading to mistimed actions and missed opportunities. To make matters worse, FC 24 suffered from poor optimization, evident in excruciatingly long loading times and sluggish menu navigation.

In summary, from performance issues and server disconnects to lackluster gameplay and subpar optimization, it was a letdown. Potential buyers should exercise caution before investing time and money into what should have been an engaging gaming experience.

Have you ever wanted to play a sports game where the "athletes" you are controlling act as if they have never actually played the sport the game is allegedly portraying? Then this is the game for you.

If you try to play a long pass but under hit or over hit the pass(hold down the button the wrong amount of time), then your player will just play the ball randomly to one of your players in a direction you aren't even facing. Much like real life, where when a professional player plays the ball with the wrong amount of pace, it actually goes in a different direction.

If you have two players on your team near each other(which happens all the time bc players in this game make the same exact run as each other even in a 3 v 1 situation), and one of those players is has coverage, it is better to not make the pass at all because you will play it to the opponent who is covered EVERY TIME.

I wouldn't consider Y to be a through ball anymore its actually just the button you press to give the ball to your opponent(along with most other buttons).

L is supposed to shield the ball or jockey your player, and it also scissor kicks every cross that doesn't make it your way. So pretty much if your jockeying for position on a cross you will scissor kick it EVERY TIME. (to be fair, this has been consistent across FIFA games forever, which makes perfect sense considering how often you see people scissor/bicycle kick corner kicks)

If you are caught on the break and the opponent is rushing up one of your flanks, good luck switching to your left back or right back. First you must switch between your two center backs and a defensive midfielder halfway up the field(thinking he's a striker?) 4 to 5 times. Then when you finally switch to the guy who would actually do the defending in ANY real life scenario, the player is beyond him. 

You know when you're watching the prem and its a one on one situation with the keeper and the keeper, rather than actually try to stop the ball, just jumps in the air or throws his arms straight up without moving side to side or trying to make themselves bigger and then the opponent scores every single time?

Again, why does EVERY single player not seem to know what sport they are playing? And its like, you buy a player, knowing what style they play and their strengths (both in real life and according to the game) and yet they act like complete fools. I can not tell you how many times Erling Haaland runs to the corner to receive the ball in a 2v1 situation rather than crashing the box(and I specifically have custom tactics for him to do this), or Christian Erickson can't make a 5 yard pass to one of his two teammates near each other because one of them is being defended. Very reminiscent of real life.

[h1][u]FIFA 24[/u][/h1]

Stepping into FIFA 24 as a newcomer, I found the Career Mode's potential intriguing, yet some aspects left me wanting more.

[b][u]Pro:[/u][/b]
+ Accessible and inviting gameplay, especially for beginners.
+ Career Mode has promising features that draw players in.

[b][u]Contra:[/u][/b]
- Some illogical elements in Career Mode detract from the managerial experience.
- The game's significant price drop just 5 weeks after release raises questions about its value.

[b][u]Conclusion:[/u][/b]
Despite some shortcomings in Career Mode, FIFA 24 offers an [u]GOOD[/u] soccer experience for newcomers. The quick price drop post-release, though, is a reminder of why I'm usually cautious with EA games.

Ever wondered what would happen if your football ball joined a salsa class? Welcome to EA FC 24, where even the ball's got moves smoother than my weekend dance floor attempts.

Graphics so realistic, I've started a virtual apology tour for every unintentional somersault my player does. FIFA regulations apparently frown upon football acrobatics – who knew?

Career mode is a wild ride. Sign a fat contract one minute, get a virtual red card for an overenthusiastic cartwheel celebration the next. Note to self: stick to soccer, leave gymnastics to the pros.

The soundtrack turns your living room into a disco, urging you to celebrate goals like nobody's watching. Just hope your neighbors appreciate your virtual moonwalk skills.

Opposing team's goalie? More unpredictable than a cat on a caffeine bender. I'm convinced they've got a crystal ball hidden in the goalposts.

Minor quibble: my virtual manager holds a grudge. Tried negotiating a better contract; he responded by turning my player into a clumsy tap dancer for three matches straight.

In short, EA FC 24 is a crazy combo of football, dance, and unexpected plot twists. Laugh, cry, and question your life choices – just keep that virtual ice pack handy for those unexpected virtual injuries. And maybe consider enrolling in a dance class.

EAFC 24 is poorly optimised for PC. I experienced very perculiar microstuttering during offline matchplay/gamplay despite having no frame rate drops (according to my on screen FPS tracker). And i've got a decent rig capable of playing CyberPunk 2077 with no issues (RTX 3080).

The microstuttering is so intolerable I had to return it for a refund. Tried over an hour to tinker with the settings to get it right but to no avail. 

This is the first time (in a long time) I tried playing FIFA/EAFC on PC and I must say the overall experience feels very unpolished compared to my experience playing it on console in recent years. There is no controller support for Dualsense controllers. So you get xbox on screen controller prompts while using a playstation controller.

I might reconsider trying this again in a few months if there is a steeper discount and if stability improves. Not sure if that is going to happen though. In the meanwhile I'll continue playing FIFA 23 on my PS5.

I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 69 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 1901 from his "uncle", so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 420 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching Tiktok. So i decided to make a Tiktok account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. It was all going so well until... I heard a loud thump upstairs. As I walked up the stairs, I saw pieces of what seemed to be a controller shattered across the floor. As I peeked behind the door, I looked at my Son and realised that he had killed himself playing this game. Now I have nothing. This game has destroyed what little part of my life still brought joy.

i played FIFA since i was a little kid... I'll call this game FIFA, there isn't any other company making a decent football game so lets call it what it is. I played 20,21,22,23 and although the game always seem like shit at the start, i get used to it and learn to play it trough its faults. But this year its different, this year the game fundamentals are truly broken. 
            The keepers are the worst I've ever seen, they get baited so easily, don't know how to dive forwards or to the direction of the ball and their hands cant grab a single shot, they defend towards the goal so it bounces in is hands and enters the goal
           Crosses, through balls, simple passes 40% either don't go with enough speed (and an AI computer guy decides to intercept, get the ball counter and score), they don't go to where you directed it or they go to someone you couldn't even imagine of it receiving the ball (making me feel like this pass was pure luck and randomness) or sometimes it feels like its aimed at the opponents players directly.
           When i make a successful  standing tackle does the ball need to be bouncing between feet and end up in the opponents possession again? is this what it feels to be realistic? the feel that anything can happen? if it is then its not the way to go. I want to feel rewarded when i do a good tackle, when i make a good sliding tackle.
            I play seasons, i refuse to play UT because they are two different game modes with different mechanics, and i want to play with the same mechanics when i do a online friendly with my friends. UT its the same play every game, cut back passes in the goal line for a easy tap in, making every game boring and constant struggle to prevent those type of goals.
            The game is less about having a even team with all above average players and more about having that broken guy that shoots a missile or runs and takes tackles like a rhino.
            I will not even dive in to the bugs it was and the freezes and speed ups of gameplay i have since fifa 23 when i try to play online.

Disappointing Experience with EA Sports FC 24

As a long-time fan of EA Sports games, I had high hopes for their latest release, FC 24. Unfortunately, my experience fell far short of expectations.

Firstly, the gameplay mechanics felt unpolished and glitch-ridden. Basic movements were clunky, and player controls often felt unresponsive, leading to frustrating moments during matches. It was disheartening to see such fundamental issues in a game from a renowned developer.

Moreover, the visuals were lackluster, failing to meet the graphical standards set by other titles in the EA Sports lineup. The game lacked the immersive quality I've come to expect, with outdated graphics that detracted from the overall gaming experience.

Additionally, the game's AI seemed poorly developed. Opponent teams displayed unrealistic behavior, making the gameplay feel artificial and scripted. It detracted from the authenticity that typically defines EA Sports games.

The lack of meaningful updates or innovative features was disappointing. It felt like a rehashed version of previous titles rather than a significant evolution or improvement.

Furthermore, the online mode was plagued with connectivity issues, resulting in frequent disconnections and disrupting the multiplayer experience. It made playing with friends or competing against others more of a hassle than an enjoyable experience.

Okay so, I've played about 250+ hours of this game and here's my honest opinion.

DO NOT BUY THIS FOR ULTIMATE TEAM.
A few minutes ago I played what I consider to be my last Champs Weekend for the foreseeable future. 
The scripting I faced in the 5 games I played is honestly unreal.
And there is only one foolproof way to attack that 100% works, which is to run down either flank, do 1-2s and pass it into the net which has pissed me off so much.

I will play this game for Pro Clubs however as I do like that mode and the more human-ness of it, if you can say so. It's just crazy how much Ultimate Team can screw your head over even if you play well. I'd rather spend my time elsewhere. 

If you do want to buy it, get it on sale when its 50~70% off. The full price is not worth it to experience the DDA, scripting, broken ball physics, not given penalties, and what not. Not to mention the way the "main" gamemode of Ultimate Team is set up to draw you in to spend real cash to get better in-game "cards" or "items" which, AGAIN are RANDOMLY GENERATED. There's a word for that and it's called GAMBLING. They just want you to keep throwing money into the game. So better to not waste your efforts and whatnot on making an "ultimate" team that will belong to a game that's dead come next football season.

If you do get the game, stay away from Ultimate Team, especially Champs and stay sane. Peace.

I encountered a hacker in one of my games. I reported him to EA and got an e-mail that read: "We reviewed your report and didn't take any action this time."
This is how EA deals with hackers. By not banning them, but they do ban people who sell players on the marketplace for maximum asking price. Not only is the max. asking price something EA themselves decide, they are the reason why certain players boom in price.

The game just isn't fun anymore, plain and simple. The only ones who still play it are the people who are addicted to the packs and that one in a hundred games that happen in-game that actually makes you feel like a God player. Even though you're actually not, you're just playing a player who has bad connection because EA servers suck.

The only positive is actually the menus. There's plenty to do and plenty packs to grind for without having to give EA money, but trust me, they do try their hardest to make you buy them.

We all know what kind of company we're dealing with by now, but please do consider your mental health before giving them any of your money, because EA absolutely don't care about it and even promote more toxicity in-game making the EA FC community one of the most toxic communities in gaming. It's just not worth it, even at a discounted price.

The game does not reward knowing game mechanics, fundamentals of football, nor does it hold any kind of competitive integrity. The stats for the players do not affect the way the players play. Pace does not dictate how fast the players are, defending stats do not dictate how good a player defends at least in online play. What dictates the way the game works is the dynamic difficulty adjustments that are made by the game's engine in order to "balance" play. Being the top rank in the game is not about how well you play it and is more dependent on how much you play. Instead of matching players of equal skill level the game matches two players and turns the AI intelligence way up or way down for one of or both of the players.

It really sucks watching you favorite defenders jump out of the way of shots while you are jockeying to block, your favorite attackers slow down as soon as someone follows 3 meters behind them, and your favorite midfielders pass the ball directly to the feet of the opposition players when trying to get a through ball over just because the game engine decided that the 4'9" defender can win the aerial battle versus 6'2" striker.

The only reason the play the game is to play the single player modes and if you have any FIFA game after FIFA 12, you basically have this game, except in the other ones you can play the world cup.

If this game were to get rid of the DDA and were to introduce SBMM then it would be a good game, however that would require EA to be a community oriented game developer and that's not what they're about.

After reading all of the reviews I had to try this game out since it was on sale. I would like to say I have decided to refund the game which I will elaborate on after but I still recommend it. I primarily play career mode and kick off (normal games). Been playing FIfa games since I was little. I think there are MANY good additions to this game animation wise. I did not experience any of the tech issues other people were having and my system isnt anything super powerful. 6700 core gfx and i5-13500 cpu. The main issues I had with this game were two-fold. One being that the AI on defense is awful. I play on max difficulty settings with what I like to call (realistic) sliders for cpu and for me. Basically slowing the speed of the game down and making mistakes more common. I played a couple games trying different things but I tried Chelsea (my favorite team) vs Arsenal. I was able to score 9 goals against max difficulty AI with realism sliders. This is awful. The other issue I had was the midfield. The midfield feels non-existant. Most plays I made were just flying right through the midfield and the build up was none. Its just end to end. I hope in the next version of the game this improves. For most people this game is excellent and a great change compared to the past few games.

FIFA is dead; long live FIFA. EA’s football simulation behemoth has returned for one last hurrah after a nasty public divorce with its licensor, calling itself ‘The World’s Game’ ahead of a painful name change to EA Sports FC, coming next year. But the tagline transcends its bittersweet pomp because, for all intents and purposes, FIFA 23 fittingly does feel like the same game the world has been playing for the past few years, with its reliable end-to-end gameplay and familiar frustrations.

Even at the end of an era, FIFA 23 marks another year of careful attrition from EA, as several tactical and aesthetic revisions supplement its sturdy gameplay blueprint. Yet it’s also an entry that feels both propped up and consumed by its Ragnarok status, begrudgingly pulling down a ruby-red final curtain as the football game genre descends into a maelstrom of chaos.

Poorly optimised for PC. I would recommend playing this game only after a massive update for bug fixes and feature implementation for some of the things I've mentioned below.

1 - Lagging, freezing or stuttering after each and every corner kick for a few seconds (which are very important in a game in which you are down 1 goal in min 87 for example). 
That stupid 2 seconds lag/stutter after executing a corner kick is heartbreaking, I mean, why would you do this? 

2 - Another annoying bug (feature for EA) is in Career Mode - Manager. 
If you exceed expectations on every objective, aside from the least important one, the relationship between you and the board worsens by each day, until when you click Finish Season, you are at half (or below). I exceeded ALL important, crucial objectives, but for the low one, I didn't raise the average age level of the team to 28, therefore I on thin line to get fired, or eventually get fired (even after winning an European competition, the title and the cup, and making over 50 mil in profit). 

3 - Not mentioning the fact that I DON'T HAVE THE TEAM LINEUP PRESENTATION anymore! This is a BIG minus from my side.
I always liked to look at the team I've built, the team I'm up against, the table/position I'm in etc. Taking this out and substituting it with idiotic drum beating or people screaming on the street is enraging. In Champions League the whole atmosphere was give by that presentation, hymn and everything. 

I'm sure I've encountered many more annoying "features" but I can't remember them right now.

Nevertheless, I guess many bugs will be fixed in future updates, as these types of issues discourage players like me, who like to play in Career mode - Be a Pro or Manager.

I Played Ea 24 on a Switch for months. Now, I have decided to upgrade my experience and this is def a better, smoother gameplay. On Switch the players seem like they are playing Hockey so far on this version, I  have not gone through it which is truly amazing. 

There are of course some things I do not like, such as intro cutscenes, they were for the most part, removed, I honestly would have loved watching them specially now, we higher resolution. Additionally, some cutscenes seem to have bugs, for instance every time a cutscene begins, it lags and then plays normally. It is kinda annoying I am not gonna lie. 

I wish they could fix cutscenes lagging and add the rest of the truly amazing cutscenes this game has (Basing this on my Switch experience) I will without a shadow of a doubt play this game for hours. Best advice, do not get it  on a low end computer because the game seems to run very awful on those type of PCs. Also, if you are using a controller go to settings to change game style Keyboard+Mouse to simply Keyboard. This will allow you to use your controller for essentially everything, some times the game forces you to use the mouse to scroll through some menu options. 

Additionally, this game is not worth full price, wait for a special deal such as 50% off or higher. The game is way better optimized for next gen consoles so do not expect a perfect or sleek game, and yes, you will encounter issues with high end computers. PS: I do not play Ultimate team so I do not have anything to say about online gaming to my understanding you have to lower the graphics to play it descently. 

Overall I give this game a 7 out of 10. I got it on a special deal so it was worth the money I spent on it. And lastly do not fall under the trap the more FPS the better, nope, this is a sport simulator that runs better on a locked refresh rate of  60 frames per second. It is a sport game, not Fortnite.

Story Short: game is very bad, because EA is greedy. I play it only when I can't sleep, because it resets my mind.

Story Long: FC 24 and all previous Fifas should be used on economy classes as perfect example of what monopoly does to the product. I don't even know where to start while saying what is bad with this game, but I'll try.

It's not for casuals. Really. You either need to spend a lot of $ or a lot of time to have any chance while playing with others. After my about 60 hours I don't even have class C semi under meta single player. I know - you can say, 60h in 3 months ? only ? For Fifa players 60h is like nothing. 

The other thing is matchmaking. Matchmaking not based on skill-ELO rating should be legally banned. It causes frustration. In one division I am winning (almost) every match. I feel the frustrations of opponents. Pausing all times. Sending me friend requests after match they lost 0:8 only to relieve their pain by insulting me, and my ancestors 20 generations earlier. Then.... I advance to next division and I loose 30 matches in a row having no chance with much better players. And there's no relegation :) So I need to on purpose forfeit matches only to stay in lower divisions. Sorry, I don't have 10000h in life to learn all the skill moves to compete with people who play it 1000000 hours every year. I just want to play even matches with people on my average level. I want to have 3:3 in match. Not 8:0 or 0:8. Game is supposed to be fun. Losing 30 matches or winning 30 matches in a row is not fun. It's either frustrating or boring. That's why all competitive games in the world implement ELO. But EA does not have to - it has monopoly, people will play it anyway because of love to the football.

Btw. it's no surprise how EA works if it's CEO for years was the same guy who destroyed Unity.

Another thing is the price: every year Fifa is one of the most expensive games on Steam.... and still it has micro transactions. You pay for the game and then you need to either invest a lot of money or crazy amount of time to be able to actually play it - otherwise meta teams will just crash you. Seriously ?

I will still play it, because I love football. But it's just crazy that there's no competition and EA may do whatever. Monopoly.

[h3]Background[/h3]

I [b]have prior experience[/b] playing and enjoying football simulators, and this isn't my first encounter with the genre or the specific franchise. As a football enthusiast, my expectations were quite low, especially after reading some reviews. Nevertheless, I approached the game with interest and hope for a positive surprise. However, I [b]cannot recommend this game[/b] unless you fall into a very specific group of people, which I will elaborate on in this review.

Let's delve into the three most prominent game modes, which essentially encompass about 99% of the game's content.

[h3]Ultimate Team[/h3]

If you've ever witnessed people playing slots in Las Vegas, this mode might evoke similar feelings of shame and disgust. It's advisable to reconsider and [b]seek help[/b] if you find yourself going down this path.

[h3]Career Mode[/h3]

This mode should constitute the majority of your gameplay if you lean towards a power trip style of play. Progress, change leagues, build a team, win titles, and more. You even have the flexibility to adjust sliders and difficulty for a challenging experience against the computer.

[h3]Clubs[/h3]

On paper, this mode appears highly promising. You can choose a role, team up with friends, play together, lead your team to higher leagues, claim trophies, enhance your character, customize appearance and skills to match your gameplay, and compete against other teams. Sounds super fun, right? Well, here's the catch...

[h3]The Catch - Main Thesis[/h3]

The game is [b]evidently flawed[/b]. While it claims to be a football simulator, it's more of an [b]exploit simulator[/b]. If you don't conform to the prevailing trends in team composition and player abilities, centered around what is exploitable, you'll find yourself unable to compete against those who do. YOU WILL LOSE. Learning and executing exploits becomes a necessity, and while there are numerous tutorial videos available, succumbing to this approach can ruin the overall gaming experience.

Allow me to provide some examples that resonate with around 90% of the player base. The game's current form, and as per discussions with other players, past and possibly future iterations, is highly exploitable. Consequently, you'll witness only three types of goals in this so-called football simulator.

1 - Players exploiting the sides of the pitch, executing either a cross (Beckham's to Ronaldo vs Zaragoza) or a series of cheap passes systematically positioned between your defenders.

2 - A finesse/trivela kick from the corner of the box (Quaresma style), always resulting in a goal due to a bug in goalkeeper positioning.

3 - A messy first-post header from a corner, forcing you to move the goalkeeper around the box while the opponent reverts to the aforementioned alternatives.

While you may score and witness hundreds of goals like these, the game's rigidity to these play styles and game-breaking mechanics eradicates the sense of being immersed in a football simulator. It feels more like a game of [b]"exploit or perish."[/b]

[h3]To wrap it up[/h3]

Frankly, I anticipated much more from the purported best-in-industry and expensive game. This disappointment isn't solely based on the gameplay; it extends to actual bugs involving matchmaking, glitched menus, automatic configuration reverting, uniform malfunctions, a community rife with sore losers resorting to excessive sliding tackles and leaving matches when behind, glitched animations, inexplicable computer decisions, alleged handicapping of matches, and other issues that my friends and I endured to play this game.

In summary, and being entirely candid, I [b]strongly advise against[/b] subjecting yourself to this experience.

[h3]That being said...[/h3]

... there's one exception though: if you happen to be a die-hard fan of the franchise for decades, maintaining a close-knit group of friends who play it year after year, regardless of the game's price or condition. If that's the case, go ahead; perhaps the camaraderie with your friends will provide moments of laughter, temporarily diverting your attention from the overall mess that this game truly is.

Unless suffering is the direct and immediate object of life, our existence must entirely fail of its aim. It is absurd to look upon the enormous amount of pain that abounds everywhere in the world, and originates in needs and necessities inseparable from life itself, as serving no purpose at all and the result of mere chance. Each separate misfortune, as it comes, seems, no doubt, to be something exceptional; but misfortune in general is the rule.

I know of no greater absurdity than that propounded by most systems of philosophy in declaring evil to be negative in its character. Evil is just what is positive; it makes its own existence felt. Leibnitz is particularly concerned to defend this absurdity; and he seeks to strengthen his position by using a palpable and paltry sophism. It is the good which is negative; in other words, happiness and satisfaction always imply some desire fulfilled, some state of pain brought to an end.

This explains the fact that we generally find pleasure to be not nearly so pleasant as we expected, and pain very much more painful.

The pleasure in this world, it has been said, outweighs the pain; or, at any rate, there is an even balance between the two. If the reader wishes to see shortly whether this statement is true, let him compare the respective feelings of two animals, one of which is engaged in eating the other.

The best consolation in misfortune or affliction of any kind will be the thought of other people who are in a still worse plight than yourself; and this is a form of consolation open to every one. But what an awful fate this means for mankind as a whole!

We are like lambs in a field, disporting themselves under the eye of the butcher, who chooses out first one and then another for his prey. So it is that in our good days we are all unconscious of the evil Fate may have presently in store for us – sickness, poverty, mutilation, loss of sight or reason.

No little part of the torment of existence lies in this, that Time is continually pressing upon us, never letting us take breath, but always coming after us, like a taskmaster with a whip. If at any moment Time stays his hand, it is only when we are delivered over to the misery of boredom.

But misfortune has its uses; for, as our bodily frame would burst asunder if the pressure of the atmosphere was removed, so, if the lives of men were relieved of all need, hardship and adversity; if everything they took in hand were successful, they would be so swollen with arrogance that, though they might not burst, they would present the spectacle of unbridled folly—nay, they would go mad. And I may say, further, that a certain amount of care or pain or trouble is necessary for every man at all times. A ship without ballast is unstable and will not go straight.

Certain it is that work, worry, labor and trouble, form the lot of almost all men their whole life long. But if all wishes were fulfilled as soon as they arose, how would men occupy their lives? what would they do with their time? If the world were a paradise of luxury and ease, a land flowing with milk and honey, where every Jack obtained his Jill at once and without any difficulty, men would either die of boredom or hang themselves; or there would be wars, massacres, and murders; so that in the end mankind would inflict more suffering on itself than it has now to accept at the hands of Nature.

In early youth, as we contemplate our coming life, we are like children in a theatre before the curtain is raised, sitting there in high spirits and eagerly waiting for the play to begin. It is a blessing that we do not know what is really going to happen. Could we foresee it, there are times when children might seem like innocent prisoners, condemned, not to death, but to life, and as yet all unconscious of what their sentence means. Nevertheless, every man desires to reach old age; in other words, a state of life of which it may be said: “It is bad to-day, and it will be worse to-morrow; and so on till the worst of all.”

If you try to imagine, as nearly as you can, what an amount of misery, pain and suffering of every kind the sun shines upon in its course, you will admit that it would be much better if, on the earth as little as on the moon, the sun were able to call forth the phenomena of life; and if, here as there, the surface were still in a crystalline state.

Again, you may look upon life as an unprofitable episode, disturbing the blessed calm of non-existence. And, in any case, even though things have gone with you tolerably well, the longer you live the more clearly you will feel that, on the whole, life is a disappointment, nay, a cheat.

If two men who were friends in their youth meet again when they are old, after being separated for a life-time, the chief feeling they will have at the sight of each other will be one of complete disappointment at life as a whole; because their thoughts will be carried back to that earlier time when life seemed so fair as it lay spread out before them in the rosy light of dawn, promised so much – and then performed so little. This feeling will so completely predominate over every other that they will not even consider it necessary to give it words; but on either side it will be silently assumed, and form the ground-work of all they have to talk about.

He who lives to see two or three generations is like a man who sits some time in the conjurer’s booth at a fair, and witnesses the performance twice or thrice in succession. The tricks were meant to be seen only once; and when they are no longer a novelty and cease to deceive, their effect is gone.

While no man is much to be envied for his lot, there are countless numbers whose fate is to be deplored.

I purchased EA FC 24 from Steam with high hopes, being a fan of the series, but unfortunately, my experience has been far from enjoyable due to severe performance issues.

The game runs smoothly for the first 60 minutes, but after that point, it becomes virtually unplayable. Despite tweaking graphics settings and lowering the resolution to the lowest possible, I still encounter persistent lagging and freezing, making it impossible to fully enjoy the gameplay.

I invested 7 hours into the game, hoping the issues would resolve, but to no avail. The lack of optimization is evident, and it significantly impacts the overall experience. It's disheartening to see a game with such potential fall short in delivering a seamless and enjoyable gaming experience.

I understand that not all games can be flawless, but the extent of the performance issues in EA FC 24 goes beyond what can be considered acceptable. It's disappointing to spend time and money on a game only to encounter such frustrating technical problems.

I sincerely hope that the developers address these issues with future updates, as I believe the game has the potential to be great if the performance is optimized properly. Until then, I would caution others considering this purchase, especially if they value a smooth and uninterrupted gaming experience.

To start: i don't recommend the game. It's riddled with bugs not only in the gameplay, but there's a lot of visual bugs in the UI. The UI also makes no sense and is just a clutter. 

Microtransactions are back in full force, and EA are shoving out untradeable packs in the shop. Not only do they want to sell you digital goods that are worthless in a year, but they also want to sell you digital goods that might be useless immediately as you pack them. 

Ultimate team gets most of EAs little attention and the other game modes are usually left in the dust. The only positive part about this iteration is improvements to pro clubs and a few for player career. Bugs takes way too long to fix.

The gameplay feels sluggish and non responsive. While this matter is highy subjective, it is in my opinion the worst FIFA/EAFC ever made regarding gameplay. 

Conclusion: 
The game is really bad, and EA keeps pushing the microtransactions they make billions off with barely any of the money going back in to the game to make it better. The game is riddled with bugs and it takes forever to fix them, if they ever get fixed at all. It just screams lazy, and it's unacceptable that a multi billionaire company such as EA can churn out this garbage with no effort each year.

Here is a couple of reasons why NOT to buy this game:
- There is A LOT of button delay when playing online. Passes will often take off a full 1.5-2 seconds after you've given the button imput.
- There is a clear and obvious cheating problem that, even after 5 YEARS of me playing this game on this platform, still has not been addressed.
- The unfixable frame drops that affect like 30% of players, including me of course.
- The no-loss glitching that yeets you out of already won games, after which it gives you 'Oh we don't know what happened' message and gives you either the loss or a game that counted towards EVERY SINGLE ONE OF YOUR PLAYERS AND OBJECTIVES but of course DIDN'T towards any rewards.
- It is complete RNG whether or not you'll win an online match. It's almost as if the servers actively try to give you or your opponent an edge through 'passing errors' that the AI make.

There is nothing enjoyable about this game anymore. I for sure will not buy this game again, and I advise you not to either.

Honestly, I really like FC 24. Ultimate team does have some issues from what I see, however I don't play it all too much so I don't know those issues first hand. I do however really like manager mode and having the sim matches act like a Football Manager style screen. I know I could just go play Football manager if i wanted, but it's nice to be able to jump in and play as well as monitor the game.

Player career is the same as usual, it's always been fun starting with a low team like say English league 2 and working your way up. 

My biggest thing for getting it this year was finally crossplay. My nephew plays on his PS5 and I can play with him on my PC, be it on Ultimate team or pro clubs.

I know it's another yearly release and EA aren't always the best with their Fifa games, or FC this year, but I am really enjoying this game and it's a step up from previous games.

I am absolutely furious about the no commentary bug on FC24. It's beyond frustrating to invest time and energy into a game, only to have such a crucial aspect of the experience stripped away. The absence of commentary diminishes the immersion and atmosphere that is integral to the gameplay. It's a glaring oversight that should have been addressed before release. This bug has left me feeling incredibly disappointed and it's disheartening to think that such a fundamental issue slipped through the cracks.

I've been playing football games and Fifa since 90's.

This is the absolutely worst football game by EA.
This years FC24 edition seems different from previous ones because of one noticeable issue. Gameplay is decent but performed actions, passes, shots, tackles etc seem to be much more clunky than before. Also the DDA seems to kick in way harder. I feel really bad scoring 2-0 in very early match, it feels like it's always going to end something like 3-6 when DDA gives the boost for opponent. Yep, my tin foil hat is on.

I believe "clunkiness" is part of DDA and game constantly determines, for example, wether a pass should be delivered to own player or to opponent. This causes unsatisfying interceptions and also "wow I didn't actually try and/or deserve this"-feeling when sometimes DDA kicks in for me and unbelievable pass completes. Game this year is lacking the satisfying feeling that you've played well or built a good attack. Don't really need to meantion winger+cutback methods...

Is there DDA in competitive multiplayer matches and why would EA make it so?

- Money. More even the matches are, winning or losing, more money people spend on average. Equal matches make people keep playing and want to improve their teams. Huge losses cause players to quit the game and they are worth 0$ to EA. This is nothing new, online gaming has even patented ways to make online matches artificially even and giving players feeling that they should spend money.

In corporate point of view, it would be very stupid to not optimize matches as equal as possible, giving players good feelings and incentive to spend money to FC Points. No board of directors in company this big will ever say "it's ok let players play fair and let's take whatever they want to spend". No way. Any such director would be fired on spot. They optimize the player experience if they are even remotely smart.

In players point of view, this of course is very disrespectful and scummy behaviour.

So why this year passes and gameplay feels unsatisfying and clunky? I believe it's the same reason as poor quality of menus, bugs and UI crap. They are doing the minimum they can get away with. Same logic goes to gameplay and DDA especially. Of course it would be possible to use DDA so discreetly or smoothly that players don't notice it, but it would take way much more work, causing metric tons of expenses. Not really what EA does in other fronts, they want to spend the minimum.

Solution? Maybe call them out for DDA. Ask for fair matches. Ask for fair pricing models. Vote for loot box bans in your countries. Any other ideas? Share them in comments!

Ps. I don't care how many wins I get in WL. I just want fair matches, even endin 0-0 or 0-1. I want decent quality product and fair monitization. I want to be relegated in divisions, finding my own skill level and working my skills from there.

The game outside of UT is perfectly fine, besides the changes made to the training grounds.
Ultimate Team is now even more P2W than it has been any other year. From the very start the big big packs that we wouldn't see till Toty are out in week 1. The meta from Fifa23 carried over making the first few weeks basically unplayable for those that just chill and play for fun. After that it changed to 71 depth, 424/442/4231/442(2)/4222, with pressure after possession lost. This still has not been changed even after 5 or so weeks. The new Evolutions are a great concept but have been poorly executed. Within the first batch of Evos they made 78 Ansu Fati into an 84/85 that was a very cheap replacement for Mbappe with better links. Since then the evolutions have been not so game breaking until this last one where you can make Llorente even better. The DDA still rules supreme and sways matches away from the actually good to cater towards those that are worse. In previous years it was noticeable but not all that drastic to where a game would be decided on who had DDA in their favor. Not in EAFC24 though. In 24 the DDA decides matches unless you can somehow just be that much better. The best players will feel so much worse when DDA kicks in. Mbappe will feel like 78 pace, VVD will feel like a bronze, Courtious would be better replaced with the 1 arm woman. DDA is that bad in UT.

Update from 12/5/23:
Evo's have slowed down on being meta and broken and now are just replacements for recently released cards. The meta has not changed since the first week. Well that isnt true, it has gotten a lot worse in terms of play meta or loose the game. 4231-442-424-4321-4213-433(4) are now the most used with the center of the pitch being either overly congested to the point the attacking side can not play through it. At the same time the wingers, forward, and fullbacks will press anyone on the line making it so the best you can do is pass around the back, long balls over the top, or switching the full field. 4231 is the most commonly used formation since you not only have 8/10 players in the middle but also the LCAM and RCAM will occasionally push out to pressure on the line, the 2 CDM basically act as 2 CB and are most commonly the only players most will use to defend besides an occasional fullback. DDA is worse than ever, even worse than when I first wrote this review. You can be winning 4-0 in the 75th minute and tie 4-4 or lose 4-5 or 4-6 because DDA kicked in. Finesse shot and + are broken and the thing most based their attackers off of.
Luckily with what I have read from the new patch notes for the Holiday Update, the congesting the middle will now not be a viable meta, and finesse shot and + will have its accuracy reduced.

Update From 12/26/23
This is very close to the last update I did on my review but with a new patch and tons more new promos it felt like a good time to post an update.
After the Holiday Patch EA said that they fixed the congested midfield, pressure on the touch line, Finesse Shot and Shot+, and 3 back LM/RM. Congested midfield is true, it isn't as bad as it was but Pros have figured out tactics to counter the patch and share it with the public. This luckily is still very open in the middle. Pressure on the touch line isn't as heavy unless against a 5 back or 424. Finesse shot and + do not seem like that took any hit by the recent patch, they are still broken and now players are seeing this and deciding to hit it from 30+ yards out. Power headers were hit too hard, now the accuracy is terrible to the point itd be better to just play a corner short. 3 backs are now almost completely useless and back to the way they used to be. So all in all EA did a good patch that has mostly made the game tolerable again and semi-playable. DDA still runs all games and decides who wins and looses before kick off. If EA were to actually read reviews and see this all I'd ask is to fix DDA in UT and don't make it a thing. It is holding good players hostage in lower divisions because it is making their players hard to play with and letting the opposition win. When in reality it shouldn't be there and players should be able to climb back up tho their real ranks so that the lower ranks are for the actually bad players.

[h1]  FIFA 24 Falls Short of Its Predecessor [/h1]

[b]Having played FIFA 24 since its release, it's becoming increasingly challenging to maintain my enthusiasm for the game. Numerous gameplay issues and menu glitches make it hard to ignore the stark contrast between this year's installment and the previous one. [/b]

[h2]The Inclusion of Women in Ultimate Team[/h2]
[b]The decision to incorporate female football players into Ultimate Team, competing alongside their male counterparts, raises legitimate concerns. It's not about being misogynistic; it's about the game's realism. It's hard to believe that a female football player can outmuscle or outjump a defensive powerhouse like Van Dijk. A more acceptable approach might have been to create a separate women's section within the game, allowing players to engage in challenges for unique rewards. [/b]

[h2]Evolutions[/h2]
[b]One of the redeeming features of FIFA 24 is its evolution aspect. However, it's disappointing to see some cards being sold at exorbitant prices despite being well behind the meta curve. This can be frustrating for players who want to remain competitive. [/b]

[h2]Packs and Microtransactions[/h2]
[b]The issue of packs and microtransactions is spiraling out of control. In the past, players eagerly anticipated new SBCs, but now it seems that EA is bombarding us with 2000 or 3000 FIFA points packs, each costing a steep $30 to $40. This aggressive approach to monetization overshadows the gaming experience. [/b]

[h2]Conclusion[/h2]
[b]It's disheartening to observe that FIFA 24 falls short of the enjoyment I derived from its predecessor. It appears that EA's priorities have shifted more towards maximizing profits than ensuring an enjoyable gaming experience for its customers. As a player who thoroughly enjoyed FIFA in the past, it's disheartening to witness this shift in priorities. [/b]

Purchased the game strictly to play Pro Clubs and while I'm aware I haven't mastered all the (new) mechanics of the game (since my last FIFA was FIFA 14)... the game is absolutely horrific.
Riddled with bugs, extremely clunky and incredibly infuriating in certain scenarios.
There's pro's and con's to this game...but it as of right now (28/10/2023) it feels like an alpha title...not even a beta release.
---
There is a new "training" feature in pro clubs - allowing you to get up to 4000XP every week. Sounds great right? Except, once you complete the training session - the UI bugs out and the only way out of it is to force shut down the game and re-launch. 10/10.
---
The passing has all gone to crap. Forget about through balls in 90% of the situations. AI's also don't know how to through ball with majority of the balls getting intercepted by the opponent's AI.
You used to be able to use skill moves to get past AI opponents - not anymore. The guy will cover and jockey you the entire time until you take a slightly heavier touch and lose possession. The only time skill moves work on AI's is when they bug out and miss a tackle.
Set pieces (Free kicks, corners) are absolutely horrendous. The good old days when you had to use pure intuition and skill to score? Gone. Replaced with an awful "guided aim" where you have to select your curve and direction. 2.9 of a bar? Well - sorry champ, the ball drops down to knee level of the keeper. 3.0 and above? Oh, well good luck saving it!
---
The balancing between tackling and issuing commands to AI is passable at best. When you're instructing the AI to clear the ball (Press B or O), half the time you end up tackling the air yourself - and if you're unfortunate enough you give away penalties or free kicks. Outstanding!
---
As for the experience with online players? Funnily enough it's greatly improved since I last played a FIFA title - with the exception of a few, my experience has been as an overall positive.
I prefer the new system where you have to invest points in your skills (shot power, passing etc.) - but with the passing so bad, I found that there's little to no point investing your points in that skill tree.
---
There's potential for this game, but the rate at which bugs are fixed and patches are released right now is anything but Agile DevOps. I feel like this game was left with a skeleton crew to support the release and moved on the the "EA FC 25" title; where majority of bugs are still probably going to prevail and they'll sell you a new ground-breaking feature that nobody uses and everyone skips through.

Having played FIFA titles competitively and consistently throughout the last 5-6 years, I can safely say without a doubt that this is the [b] most horrific title ever released. [/b] This may seem like an overreaction (after all, how bad can a reskinned football game be right?!), and I wish it was, but it isn't in the slightest. I will break this down into some broad sections:

[h3] Gameplay: [/h3]
Where do you start with this. It appears that, for what feels like the third time in a row in FIFA/FC franchises, that the AI is only capable of playing at a high level using high depth, direct passing tactics, that completely negate any form of tactical flexibility or stylistic influence you may wish to have (this may be my FM brain kicking in, but im sure most people dont ALWAYS want to play the same 90 minutes over and over again?). Having been in the elite divisions and consistently finishing FUT champs at around 16-4, I have not seen any variation, besides the starting formation to revert to the standard 4321 meta.

[h3] Player Flexibility: [/h3]
With the new Evolution system being introduced, I, like many fans, were excited to see what layer of tactical flexibility this could offer to teams in ultimate team. Unfortunately, this feature is SEVERELY disappointing. In classic monopolistic style micro-transaction paradise, more 'premium' upgrades are locked behind what seems to be a ridiculously steep paywall (I am of the opinion that paying upwards of £15 for a single player upgrade is quite frankly outrageous). Furthermore, the restrictions are so draconian that only a select crop of players can be eligible. Take the 'Centurions Midfielder' upgrade, with an increased price of 150k coins (don't try to calculate how many games you would need to play) or 2k fifa points. The ONLY usable player in this selection that would be considered meta is Marcos Llorente (shocker!), and any other would be a waste of hard earned currency/ies. Like most years, the availability of exclusive players is so unbelievably high that you would have to wait until AT LEAST post Xmas for any hope of obtaining top level cards (and that is generous, since i'm basing this off of my experience in previous titles, having playing EVERY weekend league with consistent rewards). Would you like to use your favourite footballer, Kylian Mbappe? That is a shame, since you would need a literal mortgage on fifa points to afford just his services (lets not even get into top tier icon prices!!). 

[h3] Player Movement: [/h3]
Remarkably, even due to the 'new' engine that was blessed to us two years ago on PC versions, the level of AI stupidity is quite frankly remarkable. Positional play is non-existent to be optimistic, and downright outrageous on the other end of the spectrum. Realistically, the only avenue of scoring is (you guessed it) Step 1: Buy fast wingers with playstyle+s that offer more 'pace' than their stats suggest (Chiesa is a good example), to then cut it back on a plate. There is no variation at the top level of the game, as this is the most achievable way of scoring a goal. The lacklustre player movement also extends to goalkeepers, who not only do NOT save shots with their actual hands (more so a forcefield aura around their gloves, magic!), but fail to make basic saving animations, and often find themselves locked into animations that they are unable to get out of. We've all seen Alisson Becker make a howler as he is diving sideways, despite the ball coming straight at him (I guess?).

[h3] Predatory Marketing: [/h3]
For what feels like an eternity, EA have been very fast to implement micro transactions into their games without actually considering improving the fundamental gameplay, which in turn would give a more enjoyable experience and thus make people consider spending their hard earned funds on the game. When one of your landmark features in your ultimate team breakdown is the 'Claim All' Button, shouldn't you be looking elsewhere? New packs have been introduced which can set you back a literal weeks shop (if you're not careful). Thankfully there is some pushback in Europe from countries such as Belgium, but more needs to be done to recognise this in built slot machine, which, is also key to note, is listed as a PEGI 3 (ie. EA are perfectly morally ok with the fact that literal children could be gambling money on their game, just to get a virtual card which will be irrelevant in 12 months!!).

It is safe to say that this is the worst football game experience I have endured in a while. My likelihood of buying the next title is, for the first time ever, hit a new ground zero. I would encourage others to perform something similar until actual, effective, and purposeful change has been implemented to allow for tactical flexibility, gameplay consistency, and a fair playing field for all those who wish to play (from casual to professional players).

There are some new features I didn't have in 17 so I had some fun messing around with the newer features and everything like that. been playing for about 24 hours as of writing this. And I can confidently say I'm having a good time! yeah sometimes it makes me want to throw my controller in an active volcano, but that's just FIFA. There are bugs here and there still, but most of them aren't really game changing and I've mainly laughed when I've gotten them since most of them in my experience are just silly glitches. Some thoughts though if you want a pros and cons list:

Pros:
-Some new shit was added, hooray
-New soundtrack is pretty awesome, I enjoy FIFA17s more though
-Okay career mode, I do miss the actual career with the VA and stuff though

Cons:
-Some bugs here and there, not that big of a deal though
-Ai can be pretty goofy sometimes, can get annoying

Final Thoughts:
Hey, listen, if you haven't picked up a new game in a while, give this one a try, you can always refund it! "EA Sports FC 24" truly sets a new standard when it comes to graphics and presentation in the world of football gaming. The visual elements are incredibly impressive, and they manage to create an unparalleled sense of realism and immersion. You genuinely feel like you're part of a real football league, thanks to the meticulous attention to detail in player animations and stadium design.

However, speaking from a personal standpoint, the gameplay can be a bit of a mixed bag. The momentum/scripting system, while intriguing, sometimes feels capricious. It can be challenging to anticipate outcomes, and that unpredictability can occasionally be a source of frustration because you suddenly lose control of your player.

For example, in a match, if one team is significantly better than the other, the scripting mechanic may come into play to level the playing field. This could lead to the underdog team suddenly performing exceptionally well, while the stronger team might experience a dip in performance. In essence, it's an attempt to make games more exciting and less one-sided.

In conclusion, "EA Sports FC 24" offers an awe-inspiring visual experience for football enthusiasts. The game's attention to detail is truly commendable. On the flip side, the gameplay has not changed much from the last decade, particularly the impact of the momentum system, can be a bit perplexing at times, making the overall experience a bit of a rollercoaster.

I bought this game last week and I'm almost 20 hours in. I'm in a bit of a unique situation as a *very* casual FIFA player. For context, I only recently started getting back into the sport as a spectator after a spell of not caring at all about sports, and as such I decided to buy EAFC 24 so I can play the game in the modern day. For context, the last and only FIFA game I ever had was FIFA 15, so almost 10 years between the editions I bought.

I'm also not your usual FIFA player in that I could not care less about UT. Sure, I'll open it every once in a while, do some objectives, open the reward pack/s and call it a day. But I'm not interested in the competitive play because I'm too ass at the game. If I were to load up a friendly right now I'd get stomped by someone who's played every FIFA since they were born and already has a team of icons and heroes and trailblazers. So, I only play manager and player modes. Mostly player mode, actually. Right now I'm about 4 months into my first year at Reading, with the intention of making the jump to the PL and becoming the world's best CF/CAM in existence. 

Of course, this game is buggy. Even as a casual player, I see the bugs that this game has. It's just classic FIFA. I've already seen player models inside each other, incompetent goalkeeping, strange crowd chants for teams that aren't playing, crashes, player images not loading in UT cards, etc. I came into this game expecting this. The bar was low. But, it's been enjoyable. I've been having fun. Player career mode has been particularly fun. I've been on Legendary difficulty and am still able to perform well as an individual. It's not egregiously difficult where I can't score goals or dribble past defenders or make passes, but it's also not insanely easy where I score 4 goals every match and just farm the league. The one thing I really don't like is how the manager favor immediately decides your eligibility for starting 11. I dropped a stinker one game and my manager's favor dropped so much that I was a sub for the next three games despite me being a scoring machine, which doesn't make sense. If Haaland drops a stinker every once in a while and Pep decides to bench him for a month that'd be horrible. But I digress. And no, I don't restart games. I'm not a cheater. If my team loses, then my team loses. If I drop a stinker, then I drop a stinker.

Also, I hate to be that guy, but anyone that's been complaining about the game not running correctly has either never opened the options menu or has a really shit computer. I have a gaming laptop, so it's not a potato, but it's also not a full battlestation. The game runs fine at medium settings, hovering around 120 fps. The few times I've played online on FUT have been great and lag-less, which was something I remember very much struggling with on FIFA 15 when I had it.

If you're like me and only buy a FIFA once every few years, I would recommend this game. It has its charm and offers enough to keep you entertained, especially if you don't do UT either. Just make sure to lower your expectations. It's still EA and it's still FIFA. It's not at all perfect. But, it's fun, and that's what matters to me.

TL;DR Online modes are rinse-and-repeat of previous installations. Too many bugs/recycles that cause soft locks or diminish overall experience during career mode. Most of the new mechanics are either inconsequential or contribute to the issues plaguing career modes...
.
.
First things first, the parts of this game that function are nothing too special. FUT and Volta are decent but only because EA can dig deeper into consumers' pockets with these modes. Haven't had a chance to try out Pro Clubs or any online friendlies since my friends respect their time and money but nothing seems changed about these modes at face value.

The vast majority of problems are in career mode. The new coaching system on manager career soft locks when you go to fire a coach. Player career contract is hit or miss whether it'll actually allow you to renew or force you to settle for signing somewhere else. The required and optional objectives for contract negotiation are a welcome addition if they actually worked... Tackling rate contract objective doesn't seem to track correctly if your player doesn't take on any defensive duels to update the state beyond 0%. And the continued existence of the team possession match objective is pretty lame. Why should I be punished if the opponent AI is playing it safe with possession or my own team's AI doesn't properly mark or clear in a meaningful way to reestablish possession?

But if I want to nitpick the lack of UX consideration on EA's part a little more, I'd say the completely unchanged pool of press conference dialogues and news articles is still a big thumbs down even with a few new cutscenes for Player of the Season, Ballon d'Or, and winning leagues/cups. Is there a shortage of creative talent in Canada and Romania I don't know about that means this game has to keep all text-based interaction at a 2nd grade reading level?

And lastly, the new mechanics just don't feel impactful in a good way. PlayStyles feel like nothing more than traits under a different name. The manager career coaching helps keep players in-form but it would be nice to be able to fire a 2- or 3-star coach for a 5-star without the game freezing up. It would also be nice to experience contract negotiation as a player in a similar manner to the manager career counterpart... Worst of its series. Worst football game I've played in YEARS. Never have I seen this amount of bugs in a previous series before. EVER. I took a small break because I had enough of the bugs, and today I started up the game again. 

Played FUT Champs.
3rd game in.
I'm leading in the 87th minute.
The guy pauses.
I score a goal... 
the game doesn't PAUSE.... 
Then in the 91st minute after a random pass, the game PAUSES and stays like that for 15 minutes. Counted.

I instantly quit the game and uninstalled it. 

The ONLY good thing they've done this year is that they've made Pro Clubs cross-play. That's it. Still not worth it for me with the amount of bugs. 

Not to mention the unplayable game itself. The meta this year is the absolute worst - the only way you can score is by running down the wing, into the box, do some mumbo jumbo and pass into the centre - goal most of the time. Everyone does it, and I don't blame them. It works. It's almost November and they haven't bothered to change it, so it looks like it will stay like that for the rest of this year.

It's impossible to actually try and play proper football, I find myself often switching between my full backs because there is no space in the middle. I've tried multiple formations and tactics, and I've seen a lot of really good youtubers talk about this as well. It's literally unplayable - there is no attacking intelligence from the AI. 

Also, defending this year sucks. It feels like EA is punishing you for making good tackles. 

I was looking forward to Career Mode too.... when my fun was ruined by a bug in the Coaches menu. You can't fire a coach - if you try to do it, a menu you can't close or interact with, will pop up, so you're forced to close the game - meaning you should only hire coaches if you're 100% certain you'll stick with them for the rest of the save. 

The game feels passionless. A corporate's product. Lifeless.

Won't touch ever again.

FIFA 24 (FC 24) Game Review: Is It Worth the Upgrade From FIFA 23?

Introduction:
FIFA 24 (FC 24) is here, and if you're a die-hard football fan with over 20 hours in FIFA 24 (FC 24) and 400 hours in FIFA 23, you might be wondering whether it's worth the investment. In this review, we'll break down the good and bad aspects of the game to help you decide whether or not to buy it.

The Good:

Realistic Graphics and Animations:
FIFA 24 (FC 24) continues to impress with its lifelike player models, stadium details, and crowd animations. The game's visual quality remains top-notch, enhancing the overall immersive experience.

Enhanced Gameplay Mechanics:
FIFA 24 (FC 24) introduces improved ball physics, more precise player control, and better AI decision-making. These changes make for more realistic and enjoyable matches, especially in one-on-one situations.

New Game Modes:
The addition of exciting game modes like "Street Football" and "Custom League" offers diverse ways to enjoy the game beyond traditional matches, providing hours of entertainment.

Authentic Soundtrack:
FIFA games are known for their soundtracks, and FIFA 24 (FC 24) is no exception. The music enhances the overall gaming atmosphere and keeps you pumped throughout your gaming sessions.

Ultimate Team Enhancements:
If you're into FIFA's Ultimate Team mode, you'll appreciate the enhanced features, including new player chemistry dynamics and fresh challenges.

The Bad:

Microtransactions:
FIFA 24 (FC 24), like previous editions, heavily relies on microtransactions. While you can earn in-game currency by playing, the grind can be frustrating, and the temptation to spend real money remains a concern.

Minor Bugs and Glitches:
No game is perfect, and FIFA 24 (FC 24) has its share of bugs and glitches, which can be frustrating, especially in online matches. Some issues may impact the overall experience.

Limited Innovations:
While FIFA 24 (FC 24) makes incremental improvements, some players might feel that the changes are not groundbreaking compared to FIFA 23. It can make the upgrade seem less essential for some gamers.

AI and Referee Issues:
Occasionally, the AI and referee decisions can be questionable, leading to frustrating moments that feel out of your control.

Conclusion:

Should you buy FIFA 24 (FC 24) with over 20 hours in FIFA 24 (FC 24) and 400 hours in FIFA 23? It depends on your priorities. If you're a dedicated FIFA fan who enjoys the updated graphics, refined gameplay, and new game modes, FIFA 24 (FC 24) could be a worthwhile investment. However, if you're content with FIFA 23 and find the microtransactions and minor bugs off-putting, you might consider waiting for further improvements in future editions.

In the end, FIFA 24 (FC 24) is a solid entry in the series, but whether it's worth the purchase largely depends on your personal preferences and how much you want to stay on the cutting edge of virtual football..

First "Fifa" game I have bought in 5 years because of stale and minimal yearly improvements.
Last "Fifa" game I will buy for at least 5 years because of awful player experience and awful UI.

The definition of bad game design is penalizing the player through absolutely no fault of their own, this game does it in spades. For example turning up the difficulty makes your own players play like they have never played a game of football in their life, even though they are 86-90 rated, literally to the point they cannot make simple passes or even your 6ft4" defender with tons of defending playstyles not even being able to jump for a header against a 5"4 player with 50 strength.

Then there are the all to frequent "super human" moments where players act like they are literally superhuman, like taking the ball off you from 1 meter or further behind you, turning into Dhalsim stretching and contorting their legs to impossible angles to tackle you after they have already passed you, pinging the ball around like its a projectile and controlling it first time like they have super glue on their boots. The difficulty is also artificially increased by making successful tackles useless as the opposing player gets to keep the ball or insta-tackles you back, usually leaving you out of position and worse off than what you were.

There is also the issue of being dropped from squad battle games after the final whistle where you have won, saying the servers cannot process your request, you then get booted to the main menu and on re-entering ultimate team you are given a 3-0 loss, even though you never once lost connection to the internet or even the game, absolute joke.

The game is literally just an exercise in frustration through bad game design.

UI is just as bad, pray to god you never have to use the transfer market much, search for players with a max buy it now of 23k, says there is none, bump it up to 23.5k, shows hundreds at 23k.
Find a one cheaper and literally 99 times out of 100 it is already sold but wont tell you until you try to buy it, even refreshing the search will show the exact same card again, showing as unsold until you try and buy it again.

You would think that after 3 decades a multi-billion dollar company like EA would have their shit together by now but how wrong you would be, they have clearly stopped trying to make the game better for the players and solely focus on how to part you from as much money as possible.
