worst fifa (yes its exactly the same despite the name change) ever released.

FC 24 uses the exact same assets as the past 5 fifa games. Commentary voices, animations, customisation items, AI intelligence and much more are literally the exact same assets from FIFA 23/22/21/20 and even fifa 19.

This is standard for fifa, although despite using the same assets this is by far the buggiest one yet.

Frequent game crashes, infinite loading screens and plenty of game breaking bugs including invisible players.

As for game play... It's EXACTLY the same as every other fifa game just with updated squads and kits. The only noticeable changes is the menus and music.

Also the HUD is awful. In-game camera angle cuts the bottom of the pitch off, which is fine, but also the minimap fades to the point its basically not viewable or in some instances (free kicks) it will vanish completely, meaning if you're playing clubs you literally cannot see your player or what is around them.

Difficulty settings are unrealistic. On world class, every team plays like prime barca. On legendary, MK dons play like Barca whilst your 1bn value Man City squad have the ability of 50 rated players. Clubs AI also feel really good some games and then are terrible in others. 

Only buy this game if you want to play online with friends using cross platform. If not, just buy an older fifa on sale and use mods to update the squads. Alternatively just wait for a sale and the bugs to be fixed.

EA FC 24 - A Descent into the Abyss of Despair

If you're searching for a soul-crushing, mind-numbing experience that will leave you questioning the meaning of life, look no further than EA FC 24. Prepare to be plunged into the darkest depths of despair:

Crippling Gameplay: The gameplay is like an eternal torment. Players move in erratic, glitchy ways. Controls are a baffling labyrinth, leading to nothing but frustration and anguish.

Surrealism Gone Mad: Realism is thrown out the window as players engage in absurd antics, performing feats that defy the laws of physics and common sense. It's a cruel distortion of the beautiful game.

Endless Empty Modes: The game offers a vast array of empty, hollow game modes that promise nothing but the gnawing emptiness of a life devoid of meaning.

Updates from the Abyss: EA's idea of updates is to plunge the game further into the abyss, making it even more agonizing with each "improvement."

UPDATED REVIEW:

Please note that this is purely my experience of the game during the stupid hours I have sunk into it.

I won't be completely critical of the game and I'll give credit to a couple of things, most notably the gameplay. I like the animations and the motion of the players, they are fun to control. I play on normal gameplay speed and it feels great. Players are responsive and it is very fun trying to keep shape defensively (especially against ultimate difficulty) but with practice, you get there. Attacking is satisfying too, I like the different dribbling styles, although R1 dribbling at the time of this review is a little overpowered, but even still, I am happy that it's possible to dribble past players in this year's game and score some lovely solo goals. 

I play purely offline, as where I am currently located I just cannot get a good enough connection to have any kind of online experience.

HOWEVER - despite EA releasing updates, not one of them has combated the biggest issue myself and many MANY others face, which is the abhorrent optimisation which is leading to stutters and for some, lag and game crashes. 

I would not want to know how many of those hours I have spent trialling fixes and it is the first time in my gaming experience to encounter a game that just won't play. Sometimes a workaround will fix things temporarily, but upon the next launch, it just doesn't work again. This to me is unacceptable. They are aware of the problem, yet nothing has changed now for well over a month of it being released. The hell I've been through to sort it should never be required to play any game. I paid £80, but I feel like EA owe me a year's salary for the amount of work I've done on their game for them. Crooks.

Stutters in these kinds of games destroy any pleasurable experience you can get from it. Imagine playing an F1 game, but before every corner it stutters for 3 seconds and when it fixes itself, you've crashed into an entire neighbouring village and caused £500 million worth of damage, you'd say 'Forget it' and toss it in the bin. The same goes for football games. You need precision and reactions because timing is important. You can't do that with 3-second stutters intermittently during a match. How can nobody have seen this? I feel like Mugatu from Zoolander.

It was a new era for the franchise, a fresh start, so I allowed myself to believe that things may be different, but it just isn't the case for any of the offline modes. If you think adding cut scenes of players winning the Balon d'Or (where nobody even speaks other than some announcer, which freaks me out) and an open-top bus parade of trophies you've won (which is cool the first time, but it is the same every single time after) then you don't understand why we play football games - WE WANT TO PLAY, NOT SIT THERE AND WATCH SILENT MOVIES. Is this their attempt at making it more immersive? Disaster.

True, some promising ideas were introduced, like tactical vision and hiring coaches in manager mode, but here's the thing - that was bugged when it was released. Imagine working on a new feature, but for it not to work properly. What I mean is, that you can't fire coaches, you'll lock the game and have no chance to back out. I actually hope it doesn't get patched, because it doesn't matter, it tells us what we already know - they don't care. 

It's a shame because I think that if they'd just put more effort into it, this could've been a really good game. The foundation is there with the gameplay, and that's the heart of any good football game. But why not just stop being a bunch of fraggles and develop your offline game modes more? The amount of work they put into 'create a team' for example, which was just uninspiring, is what I am talking about. Put that work into actually making a comprehensive, immersive career mode. 'Create a team' was fantastic in the F1 game, it works in that circumstance, but for a manager mode on a football game? It isn't what we want. 

For those who can't be bothered to read all that: you'll feel just like Mugatu from Zoolander - It really is the same face.

I bought the game to try it out but like other players, the quality looks like an arcade game. Do you remember soccer pro the arcade game? I played that in the pub over 30yrs ago. It literally had two buttons (pass and shoot) and a joystick. FC24 is exactly the same visually, which is very sad, I have played FIFA22, (didn't bother with FIFA23 since there was no difference). But looking at FC24 it has gone backwards in visual content. How is that possible? This was supposed to be revolutionary, but it isn't. The career mode game play is good, that's about it. With PC I could figure out very easily the routine movements or passing options and cut them out, this is a bit more adaptive. But still, for this money, I expect magic. Sadly it isn't there. Makes me wonder if FIFA employed the actual game programmers previously responsible for the game to make them FIFA 26, since these graphics and stuttering and speeding up with lag -  it’s so so bad?
Apart from that, it still has that stupid glitch from 2022 where you can’t scroll sometimes and you have to use the mouse then it works.
All the pregame and postgame questions are exactly the same as Fifa22 – what you couldn’t be bothered to make it more realistic? There should be a thousand random questions, we have about 10… 
Also, asking how I beat the team again when it is the first game of the season? Or am I going to be out of the relegation zone when I am in the top 4 with 2 games left? Seriously? And it’s the same shit now. I played West Ham first time in FC24 and the question is what did I do different from the last game. Er, first game against them. Fix this shit please. It was annoying in FIFA22 but this is lazy. Even worse when it doesn’t know sometimes what team I am managing..
And, in manager career mode, when you lock to player, you can’t use the select button to see where your player is (like in player career mode), that makes no sense. AND the goalkeeper, he just randomly kicks the ball anywhere and you always lose the ball and get counter attacked. There should be a way to direct his kicks toward you. But, I have to run back to defence from my position and hope I am in time  for a ground pass before he launches it pointlessly forward. Often, he kicks it before I get there. That’s poor.
Overall, the CPU gameplay is much better, less predictable, but otherwise, I see a very lazy FIFA22 game. I didn’t play FIFA23, but seeing this, it’s literally FIFA22 but with worse graphics (FIFA15 was even better – how is that possible?). I don’t get it. Only the interface has changed (bright white and black, wtf?) and penalties/ free kicks/ corners are more detailed.
For me, the CPU gameplay is good, which is what I do mostly, but the rest is just the same and not worth the money.
For this money, considering what everyone was anticipating - it’s a joke to be honest. And I thought FIFA were a corrupt bunch of balloons…

For a company which stated that it will be 'new' and 'innovative' game-play is a total lie, the gameplay is probably in its worst state in years. The game overall is clunky and mechanically all over the place, you have some of the fastest players in the game getting over-taken by people with much less pace, you got strong CB's getting man handled by small midfielders and wingers and keepers who are basically non-existent. The game is totally pay-to-win, it is embarrassing that you charge over 100$ for a game which has such a heavy pay-to-win method, literally there has been more store packs then content releases. Releasing 100K+ packs within the first few weeks just ruins the whole marketplace and shows clearly the difference between EA and the community, they do not care about the health of the population and the enjoyment of the players, the only thing they care about is providing store packs with the big what if when you see "Guaranteed 85+ for two and 31 rare golds", this cripples the market compared to 5-6 years ago and just makes the game not fun, playing against the same old constant meta-teams with the same tactics and same game-play, rely on auto-defending from AI / AI charge defending, AI press and then getting to the byline and then just cutting it back in for a tap in. For a competitive game, the best rewards should be won via winning games of champs, not loading up EAFC points and going to the store. It is sad because there aren't any alternatives out there similar to FIFA with the same quality and history, the day that company comes and does better, maybe then EA might actually listen to the community and put some good changes in for the community. Rather just attempt to milk its player-base every single year with 120$ for early access, and then countless amounts of store packs in promotion periods, baiting players to gamble rather then rewarding the better players

I play solely on manager career mode so I upgraded to FC 24 mainly because I wanted to do one run as Inter Miami. I could have theoretically made it work by doing transfers on FIFA 23 until the roster was mainly the same but I decided to just go ahead and update the game so that the work would be done for me and so that I would get to try the new game. 

Game is about the same overall, but I think it got some nice updates: 
- Training is no longer required (or heavily featured) in career mode. I actually thought it was gone until I saw it as optional before game time. This was a big one for me because otherwise you were grinding for the "all As" with terrible players at the beginning of the season instead of playing actual matches. 
- The cut the scene were they walk out - I know some people gripe about it, but I like how the intro is now shorter. I was skipping the walk out almost every single time so it overall felt like it was flowing a bit better
- The new traits are actually helpful - The trait that lets you dribble is nice and the trait to get longer lines in free kicks is awesome. The latter is one that I will actively scout for because it so useful and make those free kicks less of a guessing game. 
- Looks are actually improved this time - When I upgraded for 22 to 23, the looks were objectively worse for me. In 24, the graphics are a bit nicer without requiring me to upgrade my video card. 

Overall, if you have FIFA 23 and you can afford it, go for the upgrade. If the price tag is too steep, you are better off staying on FIFA 23 until they have a massive discount on a few months. If you hated 23, then you will hate FC 24 as it is essentially the same game with a few more bells and whistles.

I have a huge love hate relationship with this game and series overall but it really comes down to the fact that there isn't a better alternative and honestly, there never will be. The gameplay for me at least has always been the most fluid and enjoyable out of any football game.

Career mode has its minor improvements as per usual, dead game modes like VOLTA and Clubs still exist, I only say dead because EA don't listen to the community when it comes to improving them.

Crossplay is enabled across the board with all game modes, unfortunately crossplay isn't available for the Ultimate Team market meaning we still have a pretty bad market in comparison to console.

Ultimate Team is really good, obviously pay to win but with enough grinding you can build a team of your dream players pretty easily depending on how much you play.

Honestly my one issue with this game is the fact that they made Ultimate Team have both men's and women's team, its not the fact that they are women or anything like that for me, I actually enjoy the women's sport, even if I have watched far less of it. It's more that for me, I have much more sentimental value when it comes to men's players and getting an ICON pop up only for it to be someone I have literally NEVER heard of, really sucks. In my opinion they should be put into two different game modes based on this alone but then you could argue that you are setting that mode up for failure given the fact the women's version of the sport is far more unpopular.

Put it this way, if I pack 93 Rated Ronaldinho I am waking up my entire household at 3AM, if I pack 93 Rated Mia Hamm, I'm shrugging it off because there is absolutely NO sentimental value for me.

Overall though, its an EA Sports game, you know what you are getting into, huge focus on the Ultimate Team game mode, pay to win aspects or endless grinding and a usually stable, enjoyable arcade experience.

First of all I want to point out I only play career mode and none of the online features.
I really tried to like it. So much so I went to EA Play Pro once my trial was over so I can give it a chance. Spent around 10-15 hours in it and it is over for me. 

[b]So what is wrong with it?[/b] It's just bad. Very clunky, gameplay is super slow and weird. Defending is non-existent to the point that your defender is running away from the attacker, the AI is so scripted the ball literally goes through your defenders like they are ghosts and it is just visible the game decides "oh you are losing this one". Horrendous. I don't think I should use sliders to compensate for the incompetence of EA to actually make their AI either good or bad, but not just switching from slow and confused to rocket in a second. I play FIFA since 05 and this is by far the worst scripted one. And last but not least, it just feels like an arcade game, no cutscenes at the start of a match? Why? Who thought that career mode players would want that??? Anyways, this is the first time I am actually downloading the previous game so I can atleast play some football. I can honestly say at this state FC24 is by far the worst product EA could've come up with. 

[b]Posting my original review, so people can see I actually wanted to give it a chance:[/b]
[i]Don't mind the very small time I spent in the game, unlike many others my game runs fine and it boots without any issues. 
Also know I only play offline/career mode so I cannot speak of how the game performs online. 

Like FIFA23 I keep getting my SSD randomly spiking to 100%, making the game pretty much unplayable. It used to do it like twice a match, which was fine but now it does it like 10 times a match, sometimes it freezes multiple times in the span of one minute. I see EA "support" says we should check our disks for issues, but every other game I play goes fine and never does that. My PC is not high-end and besides those super annoying freezes it is quite enjoyable and different.[/i]

For the first few hours of EA Sports FC 24, everything feels familiar gameplay-wise, for better and for worse. HyperMotion V and the PlayStation 5’s DualSense controller feedback return make matches realistic, with precise ball and player physics, noticeable field wear and tear, and goal post-shaking haptics. It's hard to deny that there's a lot of attention to detail going into recreating a realistic soccer atmosphere. Unfortunately, the artificial intelligence part of the Hypermotion V technology that has been so heavily advertised doesn't live up to the hype. While Kinetic Shielding makes for some exciting battles, players still fall all over each other in unnatural ways. Advanced machine learning, which is pretty much a fancy way of saying constantly improving AI, is also hit-or-miss. Your goalkeepers will sometimes stand sideways and let an easy shot in or punch a ball that could have been caught, AI teammates make terrible attacking or defensive decisions that would have Harry Maguire blushing, and you'll likely find yourself yelling about an incorrect passing input more than once a match despite knowing you angled a perfect through ball with your sticks.

Wouldn't recommend spending $100 on a game that you're unable to play.

Online play is a big d1ck competition of who can exploit the most glitches. Leaving the toxic community alone and the trash glitchy gameplay, EA has decided to implement lag compensation in online play, which will punishes you no matter how good your internet connection is, making already abysmal defence near impossible, resulting every match being a goal fest 'cause no one can defend. Ultimate team is gambling sim with EA rigging the pack weight shamelessly. The gameplay against AI isnt any better, the difficulty gap between World class and Legendary is absolutely massive. So offline play is a coin toss between boring or incredibly unfair and frustrating. Online play is structured around a unfair gambling model, populated with toxic community on the back of terrible gameplay. 
It is shame that this is biggest product on the market for the lovers of the beautiful game. Football fans deserve better. Playing for the Ultimate Team. 
The addition of Women players is massive, makes more variety which will only expand as each promotion drops. Evolution is interesting which also creates more diversity in teams as you can upgrade any player you like not just meta players (more to come).
New playstyles makes pace not as important but still important, new position change makes drafts and normal games more convenient. 
Playstyles makes players more unique unlike last year where players felt generic when they had the same stats.
Haven't had the first week of futchamps but its been decent. Pay 2 win will never go away but gettin a decent team is achievable at the start.
Gameplay is slightly different, crossing is more viable, 5back and 3 back is now banned in competitive play so there should be less rats. Cutback is still too common though. The finishing is also of more variety with new animations, finesse is more effective inside the box, and shooting playstyles will be sought for (chipping, trivela, power shot).

Pro Clubs solo on pc is not working at the moment but this year it is Cross-platform so worth getting once patched.

Playing this game after paying $70 for it, I honestly feel robbed. When I first got on, I wasn't even able to play with my friends on Xbox due to an "update" causing the crossplay feature to break. Once that got fixed, we would get errors nearly every time we'd queue up for a match. We'd have to leave and rejoin the lobby every single time, and hope that it would happen to actually put us in a match. The menus are also atrocious - it seems like EA tried to design them in the most confusing way possible. It is extremely annoying how you have to enter a 10-15 second loading screen between each section of the menu. If you want to adjust simple settings, like video brightness or audio volume, you have to back out all the way to the main menu screen to do it. During halftime within games, you have to press THREE BUTTONS to skip the cutscene, with a delay between each button. I genuinely don't understand why it would be necessary to press so many buttons to perform ONE action. 

The gameplay feels really bad too. There were so many games were we needlessly lost the ball/got scored on because of server lag. The bots that are placed on your team are pretty much braindead, passing the ball to the enemy team at every opportunity. It is extremely frustrating to make impressive, difficult plays, only for it all to be ruined by a bot giving the ball away. Also, if you don't have the right stats, your character will pretty much lose every game. They will not win duels, make goals, or even pass the ball correctly if you don't have the perfect characteristics. What's the point of all the customization if only one setup will work well? I don't feel any sort of satisfaction from this game whatsoever. It is so poorly designed that trying to invest time to improve would just be a waste.

As an offline-only player that has continued purchasing basically every annual recycled edition of FIFA, I must also concede that this is probably the most substantial set of improvements to manager career mode that I've seen in years. It's not revolutionary, nor is it even as much of an improvement as it SHOULD be, but I'm also really enjoying it. Some notes for other manager career-focused players:
+ The tactical focus (e.g. counter-attack, slow build up, tiki-taka, etc.) and respective coaching staff balancing act is a modest but NET positive change. Not only does it just FEEL better to be able to have an organizing theme guiding a team's playing style, but it also makes it way easier to quickly assess an upcoming opponent's style and try to adjust strategy accordingly. And I like the *idea* of building out a coaching staff, and its current impacts are palpable and displayed clearly, but it definitely still feels more tacked on than truly well-integrated. I hope they expand on this thread a bit more in future iterations.
+ Tactical view for manager career, where you can simulate the game in real-time without directly controlling any of the players. I can't tell you how long and how desperately I've hoped for exactly this. I was glad when they implemented the top-down, circles-as-players sim option a couple iterations ago, but this tactical view is precisely what I've fantasized about!! I can finally get a vivid, fully-realized look at how the team and the tactics play out without my input, and it honestly feels more rewarding to see the team I built win this way than when I'm putting my literal finger on the scales by playing directly
+ Playstyles -- basically the "traits" system, evolved -- truly do feel like they meaningfully change a player's AI and capability beyond their raw player ratings, and better yet makes it easier for me to imagine players with distinct personalities and team roles.
+ Hypermotion: I can't believe it, but I genuinely think the animations feel tangibly improved from previous years. Acceleration, jockeying, dribbling, and other movements truly feel more natural and believable. Way moreso than in prior years when they've shoveled the same buzzword bull****
+ Though not really "new", I continue to explicitly appreciate the extensive customizability of the interface and difficulty (including user/CPU sliders as well as choosing the level of automated targeting in passing/shooting or player switching)
+ I generally avoid Ultimate Team, but I am very happy they included females in the same player pool. The whole game mode premise is pure fantasy, so why not!
~ The pre-game training session prep. Basically, you can optionally participate in the training sessions available in former games, but this time around it gives temporary playstyle benefits for an upcoming game. I like this in theory, but the lack of flexibility (for example, players are automatically assigned and you can't change which ones are given which benefits) undermine the usefulness. I still use this for big upcoming games, and it feels like a better inclusion of training sessions than in past games' fitness/sharpness balance.
- Basic and longstanding UI frustrations, such as not being able to see players' potential (e.g., "Showing Great Potential", etc.) for arbitrary reasons, like when they're on loan, their contract is expiring, or they're a free agent. Or inexplicably not allowing us to see the full scouting profile (including the text-hint for the hidden potential stat) of a player from the transfer shortlist. Like... come on.
- The fact that there is still basically no way to assess players' potential outside of the one-note textual hint mentioned above. Like, it's suddenly apparent if a player has 80 potential or above, but heavens forbid it's at 79 or they've just turn age 22, then suddenly a scout is rendered completely unable to render ANY opinion on how much they might improve. How is this still the only way?? Why can't there be a seemingly more reasonable and realistic "High growth potential" phrase or something, and/or a graph of a player's rating change over time??
- The pathetic attempts at player "personality", delivered via chat messages that only have like 4 total message options that usually amount to "Please play me more!" Either improve it or delete it at this point. It's asinine.
- The morale/fitness/sharpness system in general. It didn't feel like it added anything useful to the game, with unclear impacts on play. I pretty much set it and forget it at maximum energy recovery, and never felt the need to change it
- Some pretty game-breaking bugs, including an unavoidable where the menu interface permanently locks when you try to fire a coach (which you will almost definitely want to do as you get more spending money), requiring a full game exit and restart. I've literally stopped playing for the moment until this gets fixed, and the bug has been explicitly acknowledged by EA for several weeks but still hasn't been patched. Even for EA, that's low.

Overall: Still an abysmal year-over-year improvement from EA in basically all of their sports franchises, but I confess that this is the first EA soccer/football game in a while that has actually felt worth the purchase, for the most part. At least for manager career players!

I actually cannot for the life of me comprehend how EA get away with releasing an unfinished 'new' version of this every single year. I used to buy FIFA yearly, mostly just to play pro clubs with friends. I held off on this since transitioning to PC, due to the lack of cross-platform on Clubs, which was a weird play from EA over the past couple of years - Anyway, they introduced it this year so my friends and I have grabbed a copy each. 

Holy wow was it a bad decision, the game feels worse than it did 5 years ago. It feels like an ALPHA version of the game: the servers are horrible, it takes longer to get into a drop-in match than it does to actually play the entire length of one, the virtual pro customisation is HORRIBLE, it used to be so much more intuitive and easy to make your player look like you, or whoever you want. Ultimate team is laughable, the whole micro-transaction-pay-to-win shizz needs addressing 10 years ago, let alone now - The menus are horrible and unresponsive. The new animations pre-game are just cringe-worthy, the music played before drop-in matches is too loud for the commentary, the commentary is an insta volume 0 for me - I have seen THOUSANDS of complaints online about glitches, issues connecting to games, lag, stuttering in-game, etc.

FC24 just feels like yet another desperate attempt to take your money while papering over the cracks with unnecessary and over the top features that do not improve the gameplay in the slightest. If you're gonna get this game because you play with friends, etc., wait until it's at least half the price. Hopefully over the coming months they actually update the game enough for it to be playable.

I don't normally write reviews for games but honestly i have to say, I LOVE THIS GAME. It been the first fifa since 14 i have grinded and loved the gameplay. Not only have i been playing both single player career mode, manager career mode but i have also been grinding UT. It has been a very enjoyable exp so fair. I Preordered the game and was playing it for 7 days before public release and as you can see im well over 100 hours so far. 

The game does has its flaws however 

1. The defending is some of the hardest it has ever been 
2. Running down the line and passing into the box is stupid OP and there seems to be no way to defend against it.
3. The mains are little laggy and there is a lot of button dely when in the mains themselves. 

HOWEVER there are some really good positives to this game as well 

1. The battle pass (or level system Objectives) give you a mega load of packs and really good rewards and i have to admit that it takes little to no effort to get up the lvs. You have Bi-weekly objectives where you can get 2000 xp for just playing 30 games in any game mode. You get daily xp as well which = up too 200xp a day. There is now 40 lvs for the battle pass and the rewards are really engaging as i have talked about above. 
2. SQUAD BATTLES is now 4 minutes half's meaning that the whole match is 8 minutes long meaning it doesnt take that long to play each match. 
3. THE EVOS are amazing, i know that one of them is 50k coins or 1000FC points but i promise getting 50k in this game is super easy as moment rewards are Tradable and so you can earn enough coins. 
4. The playstyles and Playstyles + make are amazing and really make the game more fun as you start to prio them for each player meaning that you can really make some amazing teams. Picking each player that fits your playstyle. 

I really am looking forward to what this game turns into over the course of the year but so far it has been extremely enjoyable. I really hope the Battle pass is just as enjoyable now when we get season 2 and the SBC's continue to being priced good and match the power curve of the game.

I can say EA FC 24 is better than all FIFA games. The reason behind that idea is game play is better than all other FIFA's. Also optimization is better than FIFA 23. Having women players whom has more strength and pace than men sounded awkward and i still think so. But having women in FUT made more playable players in FIFA and at the beginning of the game it really helps constructing teams. The new skills that players have is really OP, For example I have CR7 in my team, and he has a skill which makes him to shoot power shoots faster and accurate. It makes CR7  playable even though he is in Saudi Arabia. If you are interested in buying this game and have questions about optimization or thinking whether game play is different, I can easily tell that optimization is good, and game play is improved. But if you are interested in playing career mode only, it's not necessary to buy. If you're going to play online modes you should definitely buy.

Ultimate Team is more fun than ever I would say, all the new gamemodes and ways to get players without having to spend money feel good in contrast with FIFA 2013 or 2015. When I play online, I play against not only another person, 
I play against terrible gameplay with annoying delay before each gamepad operation.

I play against 71 deep + pressing tactic which actually broken and you cannot do anything except of ball losing.
I play against broken R1 dribbling which allow average players dribble like Ronaldinho in prime time.
I play against Dynamic Difficulty Adjustment in match, when goalkeeper of your opponent can save every dead ball, but yours can't save anything.
I play against opponent AI bots in defending, which often defend better than opponent and do some unbelievable tackles without opponent actions. 
I play against slow players with pace 60 who can easy run faster than Al Owairan with max pace stats. 
I play against my stupid goalkeeper who cannot save ball which fly right in his body. Even if I move him by right stick and match with shooting direction, animation of my goalkeeper broken and don't match with reality.
I play against broken physics, when VVD can be pushed by player which is totally less than him in one and a half time.
I play against kick off glitches when you understand that opponent will score because of strange behaviour of my players. 

If you want to buy this game to play online you should understand that you won't be able to control major part of actions in matches. In lots of cases it's not a game about "if you click buttons better than opponent you win", it's a game about scripts, handicap (DDA), glitches, bad connections and broken behaviour of players.

EA Drops the Ball Again!

Ugh, FC24 is here, and it's a letdown - big time. First off, the microtransactions are just too much. So, what could have been a tribute to soccer ends up feeling more like a costly slot machine where spending money is key to getting a competitive squad. Honestly, it probably shouldn’t even be legal.

And where’s the new stuff? The game works, sure. But it's the same-old, same-old, year after year. We’ve been yelling about this forever, but EA's just not listening.

We really need EA to take a break, skip a year, and give us something awesome and NEW next time. How about diving into a footballer’s life with a cool, open-world feature (think GTA vibes)? That would let us really get into our football fantasies and feel fresh and fun.

In short, EA, it's time to step up. No more grabbing our cash and handing us the same thing every year. We want to see something big and new – and we're waiting!

Year after year, EA, despite being one of the highest grossing video game company of all-time, you fail to actually deliver a product on release day that is reflective of its price. People are paying a premium for your games every year, and are met with some of the most lacklustre, mundane and boring features every year. Sure, you can blame us for continuing to buy the game, but the truth is, I love football. You love football. And FIFA/EA Sports FC is the only game out there that can scratch that itch. There are no viable competitors. Therefore, through our love for the beautiful game that is football, we keep buying it. And you know that, EA. That is why you refuse to actually do some hard coding in your game and add new features/improve the game.

You are too busy milking all the 12-year old FUTwhales that spend mum and dad's money on your stupid packs, which is all that ultimately matters to you in the end. You do not care that Career Mode has not been proper innovated since the dawn of Jesus Christ, or that Pro Clubs has so much untapped potential. All that matters to you, is FUT, and the whales that keep splashing thousands upon thousands every year, only for all of their players, items, to be obsolete the following iteration of FIFA/EAFC.

I would also like to point out that, despite us paying the same amount, the level of disrespect you have continuously shown us PC players is unforgivable. Not just this year, but every other year. Do not think we have forgot about the absolute disaster of a release that was FIFA 21, FIFA 22 and FIFA 23. If you are lucky enough to even launch the game, you are most likely met with terrible FPS, choppy animations, bugged out player models, and honestly, the list is endless if I wanted it to be. Speaking of lists, I am going to provide one with all of the bugs that I encountered in my first few hours of game-play.

→ Choppy animations, frames drop and becomes an eye-sore to watch.
→ Commentary does not work on launch. There is 0 commentary.
→ Player models, the hair, bugs out when it is rainy and foggy. Becomes pixelated.
→ Can not connect to the internet (whatever this means).
→ Controllers not working properly.
→ Game keeps minimising on PC.
→ The game is not opening and launching for so many players.
→ Can not sack coaches in Career Mode, it just freezes.
→ Objectives not counting.
→ Not getting XP when completing objectives.
→ The game freezes on the EA FC logo.
→ Stuck in half-time animation.
→ Game-play stutter.
→ Overall TERRIBLE performance even on high-end hardware.
→ Anti-cheat error message.
→ Media questions still make 0 sense.
→ Same animations for media interviews and transfers.
→ Same animations for injuries, etc. 0 innovation and creativity here.
→ Menu in FUT will freeze and you have to close the game and launch it again.
→ If you navigate the menu too quickly, it messes up and goes all over your screen.

Again, like mentioned, this list could be as long as you want it to be. The point is, you are incompetent EA, and you are ESPECIALLY incompetent when it comes to creating a proper PC port. But of course, because you know we love football and we simply have no other alternatives, you can keep getting away with this. I am an idiot for playing this game and "enabling it" and I know I am, but that is not going to stop me from speaking out about the disgrace of a company you run.

Also, why on Earth would you remove players walking out onto the pitch and lining up before a game? What went on in your heads over there at EA when you thought, hmm, let us replace this key part of immersion building and realism and replace it with a few stupid cutscenes then immediately throw you into the game where everyone is already on the pitch ready to go. What about Champions League nights, important finals, etc? There is no immersion anymore. You do not get to watch your team walk out, line up, with the anthem roaring in the background, your players lined up and ready to battle it out... it just sends you straight into action. This is SO stupid. As a Career Mode enjoyer (shock, I know right, cause who still willingly plays this neglected mode?) this totally kills off getting any sort of feeling towards your games, especially big ones. Mind-boggling decision. Begs the question, in typical EA fashion, what iteration of EA FC will you bring this back and market it as a "brand new, immersive feature"?

I have bought and owned all fifa releases since 2002 on the day it was released. I have paid a premium to EA every year for the fifa franchise for 21 years straight.
The game is absolutely disgusting and ridiculous. Yes they have made a few improvements like they do every year, but along with those improvements which are minimal like always, the things that are wrong with the game made me feel like i just wasted my money and time. I know there is a crazy amount of fifa fans out there, Please do not waste your money. Issues that have nothing to do with the gameplay-
*The display refresh rate settings are locked to 60fps. (On Laptop) (Desktop is Adjustable)
*The game stutters and lags and is absolutely impossible at times. This happens even on menu screens in career mode or any other, when you are not even playing a match.
*Drastic and random FPS Drops every 5-10 seconds.
I have a RTX 3060 laptop with 64GB RAM and a RTX 4090 high-end desktop. Same lag and stuttering on both machines. So definitely the problem is with the Game software itself.
This is what i get after paying a premium to one of the biggest franchises in the gaming industry. The game overall feels like it was incomplete in its development but the launch date had to be met. What a shame.  

Gameplay Issues:

* The goalkeeper in the game is irrelevant. 
* Shooting and finishing is the worst ever.
* Even though the ball control is better and there is an element of "centre of gravity" in the movement of the player in control which is nice, i still feel there is so much wrong in the overall movement of the player in control. 
* Passing is the worst ever. 
* First touch is inconsistent.
There is so much more wrong with the gameplay. And i am hoping that these issues will be addressed with an update. I would be shocked if this is how the game is meant to be.

EA FC 24 - Pushing the Boundaries of Virtual Football

Rating: ★★★★☆ (4/5)

EA FC 24 builds upon the solid foundation laid by its predecessor, FIFA 23, offering both familiar gameplay mechanics and exciting new features. Here's what stands out:

Gameplay (4.5/5): The core gameplay mechanics have been refined to offer a more realistic and engaging football experience. Player movements, ball physics, and AI behavior are noticeably improved, creating a more authentic on-field feel. The tactical options have been expanded, allowing for greater control over team strategies.

Graphics and Presentation (4.5/5): The visuals in EA FC 24 are stunning, showcasing a level of detail that further blurs the line between virtual and reality. Player likenesses, stadium environments, and weather effects contribute to a truly immersive experience. The crowd animations and reactions add an extra layer of realism to the matches.

Modes and Features (4/5): The game offers a plethora of modes to keep players engaged. Career Mode sees welcome improvements, with more depth in player development and team management. Ultimate Team continues to be a standout, providing an addictive card-collecting experience. The inclusion of new challenges and events keeps the game fresh.

Online Play (4/5): The online component of EA FC 24 remains a strong point, with smooth matchmaking and a vibrant community. The addition of dedicated servers has significantly improved the online experience, reducing lag and ensuring more fluid matches.

Innovation (4/5): While EA FC 24 doesn't revolutionize the series, it introduces subtle yet impactful innovations. The introduction of new skill moves, refined set pieces, and enhanced player interactions contribute to a more dynamic and unpredictable gameplay.

Commentary and Soundtrack (3.5/5): Commentary remains competent, providing insightful analysis and capturing the excitement of the matches. The soundtrack offers a diverse selection of tracks, although personal preferences may vary.

In summary, EA FC 24 represents a commendable step forward for the FIFA series. It successfully refines existing elements while introducing subtle innovations to enhance the overall experience. With its impressive visuals, engaging gameplay, and a wealth of modes, it's a must-play for football enthusiasts and FIFA fans alike. While there's room for improvement in certain areas, it remains a strong contender in the sports gaming genre.

When other people have problems launching and playing games, it almost never happens to me. I see all the negative reviews here, most of them are just the typical "EA bad" circlejerk, but some of them actually list real problems. I'll add on to that here with my experience with the game.


[1.] Game took 4 tries to launch in the first place. EA App keeps crashing.
[2.] When game actually does launch, it freezes on the first screen. Had to quit and relaunch again.
[3.] When I got past the first screen, I'm told to pick my club/league/etc. I can't move the thing to make any selections at all. I close and relaunch AGAIN.
[4.] Now my cursor moves! Oh wait, it's only moving in one direction and I can't go the other way at all. Close and relaunch...
[5.] Okay, cursor moves both directions, I can pick my league and whatnot. Now let's go make a player and start career mode! Oh the cursor broke again. Close and do research that shows this was a problem last year too. If you have a mouse and keyboard, which you probably do considering you're on a fucking PC, it defaults to trying to use them in menus instead of JUST the controller. I tried just unplugging my m+kb to get around this, didn't help me.
[6.] Eventually make my way into making my character, I get him just how I want and get to the main screen. I had to leave the house right after, so I save and quit. When I came back to finally play the game..... my save data was gone. My settings are not saved, I'd have to remake my player again, etc.
[7.] Uninstall and refund because if it deleted my character right at the start, I am NOT fucking around with losing actual progress down the line.


So there you go. I'm really bummed as I was really looking forward to playing this one, I skipped last year in anticipation of the new game having a new name and was hoping it would be smoother than ever. That is certainly not the case. I wouldn't even bother if you value your time, if it doesn't break immediately, it'll probably break when it will hurt a lot more later down the line.

I played FIFA 94 up to 2019. But before 2019 it was disappointment after 
disappointment. And stopt playing FIFA (any EA game for that matter)
So after 4-5 years how does the game hold up? My pro & cons.

PROS:
- It has been long overdue, but finally some costumization for own teams is back. Even though its limited, Its very welcome
- Limited stadium costumization
- the game looks okay
- I love football
- Menu's feel responsive
- I like the english commentary teams
- A few support chants are added in the game
- EA still have the licenses for the team and leagues

CONS:
- EA app needed
- 70€ not worht it
- Menu's are a mess. The game has many modes, settings, the menu system doesn't make the clutter any better.
- No commentary issue. I had to download english language pack on steam and then change my language ingame again to make commentary available. Also a brilliant move from EA to have audio for commentary off by default.
- Ultimate team: What a clutter of menu's. Let me play
- Ultimate team: Woman mixed with men? wtf.
- Not really expanded european football. It would benefit UEFA leagues in career
- Womans are in the game
- Volta is the game
- Ultimate Team is in the game
- GenZ braindeath music
- Career mode: Own team: can't choose players
- Career mode: Its basiscally the same career mode as 5 years ago, 10 years even. Only they added some training/coach training paths. It just a waste of time and it only clutter the menus even more with numbers and icons.
-pre-game intro is horrible: I like that tv broadcast experience. Now u see one player training or stepping out a bus. And a second later its kick-off. Were is the TV presentation. Presentation of the crowds, Atmosphere, player line ups are gone
- Everytime a player gets a card i get a POV of the referee. Why? I never saw this in real life.
- Gameplay: standard Time/scoreboard layout is really bad.
- Gameplay: When you score a goal or something the TV information is so fast i often can't read it
- Gameplay: is unbalanced attacking is to easy, defending to hard. 
- Gameplay: They destroyed defending when they introduced "tactical defending" many years ago. It was never so bad. players just refuse to defend or tackle and rather want to run away. If the bal is "dead" and no team has posession. My player will refuse to pick up the ball. 
- Gameplay: During a game they rather show all game faces of the goal scores intead of showing the names.
- Gameplay: Set pieces is just the same as last 10 years. The extra information were to hit the ball, and curved trajectory line can make it more easy now.
- The Generic stadiums are the same from 20 years ago. I don't see one new one.
- Career Match day: To change outfits you have to go trough multiple tabs for each game.

For gameplay, the game does feel a little more different and slower paced than previous FIFA titles. For starters, you actually have to aim directly at a player for a pass to complete (except for through ball) and aim precisely at the goal to score. Any off positioning can cost you a loss of possession or missing the entire goal. There are new goalkeeper mechanics that I have noticed help more than hurt, especially 1 on 1s. Overall, my initial rating for the gameplay is an 8/10. 

As far as user experience, I just don't like the UI. It literally looks like a preset lower budget interface. [h1] It's FIFA 23 with new lighting. Don't bother.[/h1]

I was initially excited for this, and I don't know why, really. FIFA 23 for the last couple months was buggy to the point of being unplayable, not to mention the game would randomly crash during every match. I was hoping that some of the bugs and text mistakes and gameplay issues that have been in the game since FIFA 20 would have been resolved, but no. ALL of the bugs from the last 4 FIFA games are back. At least it hasn't crashed on me mid-match (yet).

Unlike the last 4 games, this one doesn't run as well for some reason. I have a 13900k, 4080, 64 GB of RAM and have the game installed on a SSD. FIFA 23 ran at a smooth 120 FPS in game with all the settings cranked. EAFC 24 runs at a choppy 80-90. It's not unplayable, but the graphics are the same, the cutscenes are the same, the player models are the same aside from the presentation and some better shadows the game looks the same as last year, so I don't really understand why it doesn't run as well. The really confusing thing is that when I'm looking at GPU usage it's only at about 70% and CPU is at 2 or 3%, so my hardware isn't really being taxed and the game's performance is worse... for some reason. 

My time so far has been spent in Manager Career mode, so my experience with the game is limited to that, ATM. I will update after I've played the game a bit more. TL;DR will be at the bottom. As for the game itself:

[b]Cutscenes -[/b] Cutscenes are recycled from FIFA 23, which is unwelcome, as they were a massive annoyance to me from the previous game. I swear to god if I have to watch EVERY GOD DAMN NEW SIGNING doing that stupid treadmill run I'm going to lose my damn mind. And why do I have to watch as my 3rd string youth-level GK leaves the club lobby depressingly as he goes out on loan? I don't care, that's why he's leaving. I don't need a sad little cutscene to tell me he's leaving. Just have him leave. If it were a player that's been a regular starter with the club for a couple years, fine, but it isn't. The one cutscene I wish they'd kept is the walkout of the tunnel before a match where they go over the lineups for each team. That's gone. You still get to choose your walkout anthem for your club in the customization menu, which is strange seeing as how the instance where that's used doesn't seem to be in the game anymore, so what's the point? Yellow card/red card cutscenes are exactly the same animations but filmed from the point of view of the referee... which doesn't look good. I've had a couple instances where the ref's hair clips through the camera. It's also got a fisheye effect on it, like it's supposed to be a bodycam or something. Idk, it just doesn't look good.

[b]Customization -[/b] So as far as manager customization goes, they've added some boring-looking shorts, some more boring-looking shirts, hoodies, and 4 pairs of glasses. That's. About. It. I know there's more customization options in Volta for your player, including tattoos and more facial hair options (I will gladly take an comically-sized handlebar mustache) so why doesn't that transfer into the manager creator? Oh, yeah, Volta customization can be monetized and EA are money grubbers. Good news, though, EA, (and I can't believe I'm suggesting this) make the options for character customization in Volta available in Career mode and monetize them like you would in Volta or FUT. Players get better customization (albeit at a cost) and you potentially get more money. Everyone sort-of gets what they want, or at least it's consistent with the rest of the game. Kits are largely the same, some new selections, but not many. One kit option shows up twice for some reason. There are also KITS WITH SPONSORS WOOOOOOO!!! What sponsors are they? EAFC, Frostbite, Truemotion, and one other EAFC-centric one I can't be bothered to remember. There is one kit for each of them and that's it. Also, while I'm ranting: Why can't I have a color slider or color wheel for choosing my kit and badge colors? I get to choose from 10 colors for badges and 30ish(? I'm not counting them) colors for my kit. What's so hard about a color mixer option? The colors for badges don't mix with the colors for kits unless I choose basic colors, which just looks like every other club in the game. It's so lazy. I'm grateful that I can choose to customize a custom team, but there's better means of customization in other EA games. Dragon Age Inquisition is in Frostbite and uses a color mixer, so don't tell me it's not possible with the hundreds of people that work on this game every year. And how do they still not have icons for some of the hairstyles? A couple of them are literally just regen character heads with the hair on them, and one of them isn't even the correct hair. One of the icons just shows a bald head and when you select it it puts a hat on your manager. How the hell did this make it past QA? Is there even QA at this point? Probably not.

[b]Gameplay -[/b] The gameplay this year is probably the only improvement I've noted besides the lighting model (I'll get to that later). Players collide with each other in more realistic ways, They seem to have fixed players with explosive running trait actually running like a drunk slug, and the gameplay feels arcadey but not like pinball. Another addition is that when simming a match, instead of watching dots slide around on a JPEG of a pitch you can watch the game from the sideline like a manager would and make changes from the sideline.

[b]Bugs -[/b] As I mentioned before, bugs from the last 4 games and beyond are still here. Missing text, placeholder textures, flickering shadows in the background of some cutscenes, all this on top of the usual shenanigans you get during a match. In my first match alone I had a player fly 20 feet into the air after a tackle, watched another player run into and get stuck in the ad boards behind the goal, and the player who scored a hat trick went to get the match ball from the refs and the ball hovered in the air while the player walked away pretending to hold the ball. It's a mess. I don't understand how some of these bugs have been part of this game for several years and they never get fixed. It's downright ridiculous and shameful at this point. 

[b]TL;DR[/b]
I like the improvement to the match day gameplay and graphics, but everything else about this game is either a step back or the exact same as the last few FIFA's. Most of my time with FIFA games is spent in the menus between matches managing players and formations, scouting new players, so on and so forth and the updated UI just isn't good. It looks pretty, but it's less functional than previous entries. The bugs are just as bad as they've ever been and likely to get worse because EA is notoriously bad at fixing their games. They've removed things from the game that actively make it better and the things they leave in don't work properly. It's all a proper mess. And the fact they have the nerve to charge $70 for this garbage is just infuriating. Especially when I know the modes that have the predatory micro-transactions have better options to them.

I've already gone past the 2 hour return threshold so I can't get my money back at this point, otherwise I would be returning this game. The only thing left to do it to put hundreds of hours into this game and hope it gets better with time. That being said, there's not a lot of better options. eFootball is in the same boat, but with fewer licensed teams (also FucKonami) and Football Manager is little more than a spreadsheet simulator with more depth. IDK what to tell you other than go spend your money on Baldur's Gate or Starfield or something worth your time from developers that care about their games.

Completely and utterly broken. Do not buy

Blatant match fixing has always been a problem in FIFA games, however its amped up 10x in this game. If you merely press B or Circle to tackle in the box, you will give away a penalty and you will have your defender be sent off. If you don't do this, the opposition score. Every time you do score a goal, the opposition will immediately score and you will not be able to do anything about it. The ball and attacking players will literally phase through your defenders if the game decides it wants you to lose. 

As a Newcastle United fan, I obviously play as them a lot. Anthony Gordon, the fastest player in the Premier League is one of the slowest wingers I've ever used in a football game. Sven Botman STILL does not have his face in the game despite being one of the best players at a huge Premier League and Champions League club. Newcastle and Arsenal do not have their European number fonts in the game. 

Using a controller is completely broken in this game, just as it was in FIFA 23. Half the time it will work, but the other half you won't even be playing the game. Your players won't move, or will run off in some random direction, completely out of your control. In the menus, you will try to navigate and either nothing will happen or you will flick through all options really fast when you are trying to do something. You literally can't change players when trying to defend. You can't pass or shoot or anything, you will just run off the pitch. You have to then press a button 50 times for it to register what you are doing, by which time the game has moved on.

Please, please, please do not buy the game. All of this is aside from the fact its literally the exact same game as every other year. Don't be as stupid as me, do not buy. Steam NEED to allow refunds for everyone who bought this complete scam of a game

My honest opinion about the game and just so you know I'm a 41 year old gamer who's been playing his good share of video games on consoles for a while and have recently switched to PC gaming. I know most of the people say it's the same thing every year and yeah, they are right. You are basically buying an update for the teams and their roster every year with a few extra in-game animations. Almost the same thing most of you probably do when buying Call of Duty every year. Now, the most important thing about this. Am i having fun with it? So far YES! Does it work and runs well,smooth on my set up? YES it works perfectly fine with some tweaks of course (no stuttering,screen tearing or frame rate drops) So in the end it's really up to you if you want to buy it and try it (Just make sure your set up can run it please). Besides, You don't have to buy every single Fifa title every year, same thing with Call of Duty. You can always take a break from them every 1 or 2 years and you will see you will have fun the next time you buy those games. Review:
I've been a fan of the FIFA series for years, and I have to say that FC24 has blown me away once again! This game is an absolute masterpiece in the world of sports gaming.

Graphics: ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
The graphics in FC24 are nothing short of stunning. The attention to detail in player faces, stadiums, and even the grass on the pitch is mind-blowing. It's like watching a real football match on TV.

Gameplay: ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
The gameplay in FC24 is incredibly realistic. The controls are intuitive, and the responsiveness is top-notch. Whether you're playing solo or with friends, every match is an adrenaline-packed experience.

Game Modes: ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
FC24 offers a wide range of game modes to keep you entertained for hours. From Career Mode to Ultimate Team, there's something for everyone. The addition of Volta Football adds a refreshing street football experience to the mix.

Soundtrack: ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
The soundtrack in FC24 games is always on point, and FC24 is no exception. The music selection perfectly complements the gaming experience, and I often find myself humming the tunes even when I'm not playing.

Online Play: ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
The online multiplayer in FC24 is seamless. Playing against opponents from around the world adds an extra layer of excitement, and the matchmaking system ensures you face opponents of similar skill levels.

In conclusion, FC24 is the pinnacle of sports gaming. The combination of jaw-dropping graphics, realistic gameplay, and a variety of game modes make it a must-have for any football fan. EA Sports has outdone themselves once again, and I can't wait to see what they have in store for the next installment. This game gets a well-deserved 5 stars from me!

EA FC 24 - A Game Marred by Glitches and Bugs

I recently had the chance to play the latest release of EA FC 24, and while there are certainly aspects to appreciate in the game, I couldn't help but be disappointed by the numerous glitches and bugs that plague the experience.

The Good:

1. Improved Gameplay: EA FC 24 does bring some improvements in terms of gameplay mechanics, including better ball control and more realistic player movements.

2. Graphics: The game boasts impressive visuals, capturing the essence of football with lifelike player models and stadiums.

3. New Skill Moves: EA Sports has added new skill moves to the game, which adds some variety to your gameplay strategies.

The Bad:

1. Bugs and Glitches: This is where EA FC 24 falters. The game is riddled with bugs and glitches, ranging from minor annoyances to game-breaking issues. "No Commentary" bugs, freezing, and crashes are common.

2. Unplayability: Some players have found the game virtually unplayable due to these issues, having to restart it multiple times just to enjoy a session.

In conclusion, EA FC 24 has the potential to be a great football game, but its current state is marred by technical issues that hinder the overall experience. EA Sports should prioritize fixing these bugs to make it the game it has the potential to be. Until then, I would suggest to hold off on purchasing or wait for updates to address these issues.

FIFA 23 was a step in the right direction. FC 24 feels like 2 steps backwards from that. FUT PC transfer market is still separated from consoles, meaning there's barely anything to buy on PC. Mouse keeps being automatically locked in the middle while idle, resulting in controllers/joysticks not working in some menus. They removed players cutscenes walking out onto the pitch and lining up before a game, etc. There's a lot of problems I could list, but it's not worth my time.
 BTW about the Women in FUT drama: women mixed with men sounds like it'll be a fun alternative for people tired of the same, however I see why it's considered by many as 'Forced Diversity': if it was difficult to pack your favorite players before, now imagine in FC24 where there'll be a lot of extra WSL players in FUT packs. Personally I don't care but it could be easily fixed if devs separated women & men packs, so you get 10x 83+ with only women or only men, depending of what you choose. But of course they won't do it because they want people failing to pack their favorite players, more packs being opened = more money spent by players = more money for them. 
Oh and they've said they will close FIFA 21 servers in November 2023, so maybe they will close FC 24 servers on November 2026 ? And every year, around September, they purposefully take out the specials cards from the 10x 85+ packs, basically only giving you shitty gold players at the end of the lifespan of FUT so you buy the next game instead. That's a shitty move by them and I think more people should be aware of their scummy tactics.
Anyways, I'll keep playing FIFA 23.

Excellent game.  Great controls.  The ultimate team mode is very fun.  Ultimate team does have pay to win elements, but you can also play it casually.  If the pay to win bothers you,  there is also seasons mode in which you can play a team against other players online, and the game will track your progress. There are several other game modes as well : manager, club mode, and volta.  Volta is interesting and I admit that I have not tried it yet.  It is a street football mode in which you control one player online, and it tracks your progress.  I am really excited to jump in that when I have the time.  

I am new to FIFA video games (now just titled FC because of licensing).  There is alot to learn!  I don't mean rules, I already know those, I enjoy sports.  There is a lot to learn in terms of button combinations, plays, positioning, and other game mechanics.  I still have much room to grow, but am getting better each play.  One downside the game has is the lack of tutorial.  The tutorial is in a different game mode and will walk you through gameplay mechanics but it does leave a lot to be desired.  Fortunately, if you are committed to getting better there are a ton of resources available online to improve your game.

They have added women into the game in several game modes.  I think this is wonderful!  You can play the most popular game mode, ultimate team, and have both male and female players on the same team.  I LOVE IT!  Women can now feel included, and that is what we all want right?   This is a wonderful thing!  I hear EA is doing that with other sports as well and that motivates me to try out those games.  It isn't fully integrated yet.  You can not play women's teams in managers mode.  I did read an article that hinted it will be in future versions of this game.

FC 24 stands as a testament to the evolution of football video games, redefining the genre with unparalleled realism and an innovative approach that diverges from the conventional FIFA franchise. FC 24's impeccable attention to detail manifests in its breathtaking graphics, crafting a virtual football world that mirrors the beauty and intricacies of the sport itself. The enhanced player models, stadium designs, and meticulously crafted animations converge to create an immersive experience that borders on the surreal, blurring the lines between virtual and reality. FC 24's audacious departure from the FIFA formula is a breath of fresh air, introducing a unique gameplay style that is both challenging and rewarding, forcing players to adapt and learn new tactics, thus transcending the rote repetition that plagues the genre. Furthermore, FC 24 offers a cornucopia of play modes that cater to every football enthusiast, from the casual player seeking quick excitement to the hardcore strategist yearning for the ultimate managerial experience. In summation, FC 24 has succeeded in crafting an unparalleled football gaming experience that sets it apart as the definitive choice for aficionados seeking an extraordinary amalgamation of improved graphics, innovative gameplay, and unbridled fun. This game is completely rotten, do not buy it. 

The only reason I have it is to play Pro Clubs with my friends. I had  been a fan of Ultimate Team for years, but it has gotten so broken and exploity that if I was an EA game developer, I'd tell people I don't have a job, because I'd be that ashamed to be anywhere near this with a ten foot pole.

Everyone runs the same high press and uses the RB button to force the AI players on their team to rush you for tackles. It is regular to see an opponent's CDM in champs end the game with 11 intercepts and no tackles; those intercepts are courtesy of double tap RB, where a player can make their team cut off the nearest passes for the opponent - this has not been fixed in patches this year. The reality is that no one controls their own players to make tackles anymore, they just get the AI to do it with double tap RB, good old fashioned RB, or the AI doing offball tackles because of the 71 team depth setting. 

Lets not even touch the fact that they release different card promo's every week for the same players that everyone uses, and they have tons of 'special' packs in the store to get better luck packing certain types of cards (depending on current promo's), which is a blatant cash grab at your wallet. 

The scripting is no longer a myth - some of the mistakes your players will make if your leading past the 60th min mark are uncontrollable, and this built into the game by EA so that games are 'exciting' and 'competitive'. 

I cant remember the last time I actually enjoyed playing ultimate team and I gave it up in the new year. Now that EA have successfully moved away from Fifa and can keep all profits for themselves, they will only continue to get more and more blatant with this. Please do not go near Ultimate Team, especially if your a teenager.

Year after year, EA, despite being one of the highest grossing video game company of all-time, you fail to actually deliver a product on release day that is reflective of its price. People are paying a premium for your games every year, and are met with some of the most lacklustre, mundane and boring features every year. Sure, you can blame us for continuing to buy the game, but the truth is, I love football. You love football. And FIFA/EA Sports FC is the only game out there that can scratch that itch. There are no viable competitors. Therefore, through our love for the beautiful game that is football, we keep buying it. And you know that, EA. That is why you refuse to actually do some hard coding in your game and add new features/improve the game.

You are too busy milking all the 12-year old FUTwhales that spend mum and dad's money on your stupid packs, which is all that ultimately matters to you in the end. You do not care that Career Mode has not been proper innovated since the dawn of Jesus Christ, or that Pro Clubs has so much untapped potential. All that matters to you, is FUT, and the whales that keep splashing thousands upon thousands every year, only for all of their players, items, to be obsolete the following iteration of FIFA/EAFC. 

I would also like to point out that, despite us paying the same amount, the level of disrespect you have continuously shown us PC players is unforgivable. Not just this year, but every other year. Do not think we have forgot about the absolute disaster of a release that was FIFA 21, FIFA 22 and FIFA 23. If you are lucky enough to even launch the game, you are most likely met with terrible FPS, choppy animations, bugged out player models, and honestly, the list is endless if I wanted it to be. Speaking of lists, I am going to provide one with all of the bugs that I encountered in my first few hours of game-play.

 → Choppy animations, frames drop and becomes an eye-sore to watch.
 → Commentary does not work on launch. There is 0 commentary.
 → Player models, the hair, bugs out when it is rainy and foggy. Becomes pixelated.
 → Can not connect to the internet (whatever this means). 
 → Controllers not working properly.
 → Game keeps minimising on PC. 
 → The game is not opening and launching for so many players.
 → Can not sack coaches in Career Mode, it just freezes. 
 → Objectives not counting.
 → Not getting XP when completing objectives. 
 → The game freezes on the EA FC logo. 
 → Stuck in half-time animation.
 → Game-play stutter. 
 → Overall TERRIBLE performance even on high-end hardware. 
 → Anti-cheat error message. 
 → Media questions still make 0 sense.
 → Same animations for media interviews and transfers.
 → Same animations for injuries, etc. 0 innovation and creativity here.
 → Menu in FUT will freeze and you have to close the game and launch it again.
 → If you navigate the menu too quickly, it messes up and goes all over your screen.

Again, like mentioned, this list could be as long as you want it to be. The point is, you are incompetent EA, and you are ESPECIALLY incompetent when it comes to creating a proper PC port. But of course, because you know we love football and we simply have no other alternatives, you can keep getting away with this. I am an idiot for playing this game and "enabling it" and I know I am, but that is not going to stop me from speaking out about the disgrace of a company you run. 

Also, why on Earth would you remove players walking out onto the pitch and lining up before a game? What went on in your heads over there at EA when you thought, hmm, let us replace this key part of immersion building and realism and replace it with a few stupid cutscenes then immediately throw you into the game where everyone is already on the pitch ready to go. What about Champions League nights, important finals, etc? There is no immersion anymore. You do not get to watch your team walk out, line up, with the anthem roaring in the background, your players lined up and ready to battle it out... it just sends you straight into action. This is SO stupid. As a Career Mode enjoyer (shock, I know right, cause who still willingly plays this neglected mode?) this totally kills off getting any sort of feeling towards your games, especially big ones. Mind-boggling decision. Begs the question, in typical EA fashion, which iteration of EA FC will you bring this back and market it as a "brand new, immersive feature"?
